{"title_page": "Production music", "text_new": "{{short description|Stock music for film and TV}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=March 2011}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2010}}\n}}\n\n'''Production music''' (also known as '''stock music''' or '''library music''') is the name given to recorded music that can be [[music licensing|licensed]] to customers for use in film, television, radio and other media. Oftentimes, the music is produced and owned by production [[music libraries]].\n\n==Background==\nUnlike popular and classical music publishers, who typically own less than 50 percent of the [[copyright]] in a composition, production music libraries own all of the copyrights of their music. Thus, it can be licensed without the composer's permission, as is necessary in licensing music from normal publishers. This is because virtually all music created for music libraries is done on a [[work for hire]] basis. Production music is a convenient solution for media producers&mdash;they can be assured that they will be able to license any piece of music in the library at a reasonable rate, whereas a specially-commissioned work could be prohibitively expensive. Similarly, licensing a well-known piece of popular music could cost anywhere from tens to hundreds of thousands of dollars, depending on the prominence of the performer(s).\n\nProduction music libraries typically offer a broad range of musical styles and genres, enabling producers and editors to find what they need in the same library. Music libraries vary in size from a few hundred tracks up to many thousands. The first production music library was set up by [[De Wolfe Music]] in 1927 with the advent of sound in film. The company originally scored music for use in silent film.<ref>{{cite book|title=De Wolfe Millennium Catalogue|last=De Wolfe|first=Warren|year=1988|publisher=De Wolfe Music|location=London}}</ref>\n\nProduction music is frequently used as theme and/or background music in radio, film and television. Well-known examples of British TV series whose themes were sourced from library catalogues include ''[[Ski Sunday]]'' (\"Pop Looks Bach\" by Sam Fonteyn), ''[[Dave Allen At Large]]'' (\"Studio 69\" by [[Alan Hawkshaw]]), ''[[Mastermind (TV series)|Mastermind]]'' (\"Approaching Menace\" by [[Neil Richardson (composer)|Neil Richardson]]), the original theme for the BBC's ''[[Grandstand (BBC)|Grandstand]]'' (\"News Scoop\" by Len Stevens), ''[[Crimewatch]]'' (\"Rescue Helicopter\" by [[John Cameron (musician)|John Cameron]]) and ''[[Grange Hill]]'' (\"Chicken Man\" by Alan Hawkshaw). The Christmas hit single based off the character [[Mr Blobby]] uses excerpts from \"Mr Jellybun\" by Paul Shaw and David Rogers. [[Arthur Wood (composer)|Arthur Wood]]'s \"[[Barwick Green]]\", written in 1924, still serves as the theme for long-running BBC Radio soap ''[[The Archers]]''. TV comedy series such as ''[[The Benny Hill Show]]'' and ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'' also made extensive use of production library cues (many sourced from the De Wolfe catalogue)<ref>[http://runstop.de/music07.html William Brown, essay on stock music in ''The Benny Hill Show'']</ref> as background or incidental music.\n\nAmerican TV has also utilized production music, most notably with the themes for ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' (\"[[Heavy Action]]\" by [[Johnny Pearson]]) and ''[[The People's Court]]'' (\"The Big One\" by [[Alan Tew]]). Other notable examples are the [[Nickelodeon (TV channel)|Nickelodeon]] animated series ''[[The Ren and Stimpy Show]]'' and ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'', which use well-known classical music excerpts and a wide range of pre-1960s production music cues\u2014including many pieces familiar from their use in earlier cartoons\u2014which were chosen for their ironic and humorous effect.\n\nProduction music composers and session performers typically work anonymously and have rarely become known outside their professional circle. In recent years some veteran composer-performers in this field such as Alan Hawkshaw, John Cameron and [[Keith Mansfield]] have achieved attention and popularity as a result of a new interest in production music of the 1960s and 1970s, notably the 'beat' and [[electronica]] cues recorded for KPM and other labels, which have been widely sampled by DJs and record producers. In recent years some of these British musicians have given public performances of their classic compositions under the group name [[KPM Allstars]].<ref>[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article666595.ece \"KPM Allstars\", ''The Times'', 10 October 2006]</ref>\n\n==Business model==\nThe business model of production music libraries is based on two income streams:\n\n;License or synchronization fees: These are the fees paid upfront to the library for permission to synchronize its music to a piece of film, video or audio. These fees can range from a few dollars for an internet usage, to thousands for a network commercial usage. Some libraries, especially in the UK and Europe, split these fees with the composer of the music. In the US, it is more common for a composer to be paid a work-for-hire fee upfront by the library for composing the music, thus waiving his/her share of any future license fees. In the UK, license fees for production music are nationally standardized and set by the [[Mechanical-Copyright Protection Society|MCPS]]. In the US and elsewhere, libraries are free to determine their own license fees.\n;Performance income (or performance royalties): Performances income is generated when music is publicly performed - for example, on television or radio. The producer of the show or film that has licensed the music does not pay these fees. Instead, large fees are paid annually by broadcasters (such as television networks and radio stations) to performing rights organizations (PRO's) such as [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP]], [[Broadcast Music Incorporated|BMI]] and [[SESAC]] in the US and the [[PRS for Music|PRS]] in the UK, who then distribute income among their members. To ensure it is distributed fairly and accurately, most broadcasters are required to keep note of what music they have broadcast and for how long. This information is then used by the performance societies to allocate income to their members. Typically, a library will receive 50 percent of the performance income (this is known as the publisher's share), with the composer receiving the remaining 50 percent. Like license fees, performance income is highly variable and dependent on the nature of the usage; local radio usage will yield modest income - perhaps a few dollars each time it is played. Repeated use in a primetime network TV show can generate thousands of dollars. Another method, in the United States, of collecting royalties for performances of production, stock, and library music is through directly negotiating royalties with composers and bypassing PRO's. BMI and ASCAP, and more recently SESAC, no longer have exclusive representation of composers for the collection of performance royalties. By directly negotiating the performance royalties with rights holders, licensees can pay less for the performance of a cue of music, and the licenser (the rights holder) can receive more than the PRO would pay. This is because of the removal of not only the administrative costs incurred through a PRO collecting royalties, but the removal of the \"weight variable\" which pays the highest performing songwriters and composers a portion of all fees collected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvmlc.com/music-licensing/copyright-basics/|title=COPYRIGHT BASICS|work=TVMLC.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.muserk.com/performance-royalties-licenses/|title=Licensing Performance Royalties & Licenses|work=Licensing Performance Royalties & Licenses|access-date=2020-11-04| url=https://taketones.com/page/faq#Performance-Royalties&Licenses|archive-date=2014-12-13|}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/creators/royalty/us_television_royalties|title=U.S. Television Royalties|work=BMI.com}}</ref>\n\n== Market ==\nThe production music market is dominated by libraries affiliated with the large record and publishing companies: [[KPM Musichouse|KPM]] is owned by [[EMI]]; [[Universal Music Publishing Group]] library music has the music libraries of Chappell, Bruton, and Atmosphere under their own name as well as others owned by them such as [[Killer Tracks]]; Imagem Production Music (formerly [[Boosey & Hawkes]] Production Music and including the Cavendish, Abaco and Strip Sounds labels) is owned by the Imagem Music Group; [[Extreme Music]] is owned by [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]]; [[BMG Rights Management]] runs its own production music division; and [[Warner/Chappell]] (a division of [[Warner Music Group]]) owns Warner/Chappell Production Music.<ref>{{cite news|title=billboard.com Apr 2012| url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/publishing/1098075/warnerchappel-unites-production-companies-launches-new-website7}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.horizont.net/agenturen/nachrichten/BMG-Production-Music-BMG-gruendet-Agentur-fuer-Produktionsmusik-145935|title=BMG Production Music: BMG gr\u00fcndet Agentur f\u00fcr Produktionsmusik|website=www.horizont.net|language=de|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nEstablished in 1965, [[Sonoton]] is the largest independent production music library in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.professional-production.de/fachbeitraege/einzelansicht/datum/2015/05/31/sonoton-die-ersten-50-jahre/|title=Professional Production - Technologie und Medienrealisation in Film und Video {{!}} Sonoton \u2013 die ersten 50 Jahre|last=Video|first=Professional Production-Technologie und Medienrealisation in Film und|website=www.professional-production.de|language=de|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> There are numerous independent libraries that include [[Vanacore Music]] and [[West One Music Group]].\n\n==Hybrid license method==\nThis method of licensing combines the creation of original, custom music with a catalog of traditional \"library\" music under one license agreement. The goal is to suit the needs of a budget conscious production but still provide that production with a unique and original show theme or audio brand. In this scenario, show producer identifies those scenes she/he feels are most important to the success of the show, and those scenes are scored to picture by the composer. Those less important scenes will utilize the library also provided by the same publisher/composer. Upon completion, the custom music and the library tracks are licensed together under one production blanket, the ownership of the custom music remains with the publisher who produced it, and the publisher can (after a term of exclusivity negotiated between the parties) re-license the custom music as part of its library to recoup production costs.\n\nThis allows the music composer/producer to quote lower rates because they are retaining ownership of the custom music, and will have the ability to make money with the same recording in a different production later on. It also allows the program or film producer to deliver content of very high quality, ensures that the most important scenes have the perfect music, and those less important scenes are addressed with an affordable solution.\n\n==Royalty-free libraries==\nWith the proliferation of music libraries in recent years and the increase in competition, some smaller libraries have evolved the ''royalty-free music'' model. These libraries do not charge their customers for licensing the music. Instead, the customers purchase a CD or access to an electronic collection of music - priced typically between 50 and 300 dollars - whose content is licensed in perpetuity for them to synchronize as often they wish. These libraries depend mainly on performance royalties for their income (with a small amount of income from sales of physical CDs or online track downloads). Assuming that the music is broadcast, royalties are paid on the music, though it is the broadcaster who pays them via annual fees to the performing rights societies, not the producer who uses the music in their production.\n\nSome companies offer truly royalty-free music which is not registered with any [[performance rights organisation]] (also known as \"royalty collection agencies\"). These companies license music to their customers on a non-exclusive basis where it can be used in perpetuity without any usage reporting. The music is licensed by the customers according to an accepted license agreement, and they cannot sell it or license it to others. Because of advancing technology, it is becoming easier for independent musicians to set up their own shops through which they can license music.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thetechreviewer.com/tech-tips/best-royalty-free-music-websites-filmmakers/|title=7 Best Royalty Free Music Websites & Services For Filmmakers|date=2017-08-11|work=TheTechReviewer.com|access-date=2017-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Non-exclusive libraries==\nNon-exclusive production music libraries enable a composer to sign a non-exclusive agreement allowing the artist to license the same piece to other libraries and clients with the same non-exclusive agreement. In other words, their intellectual property (their composition) can be licensed to multiple clients simultaneously, provided that they are not contractually bound by an exclusive agreement with another company. The non-exclusive library doesn't own the rights outside of the licenses that are made by that library. Typically the library does not pay for the piece, and the artist doesn't get any payment until the piece is licensed at which point the library and the artist split the license fee equally. Libraries typically require the artist to rename the piece in effect creating a unique artistic work for the library to register with their PRO (BMI, ASCAP, SESAC). Should the composer want to enter the piece into an exclusive agreement with a library or client, they would first need to remove that piece from all non-exclusive agreements.\n\nAn advantage to using a non-exclusive library is the possible broad exposure through multiple outlets, and the ability of the artist to retain control. Conversely, if an artist sells his/her piece to an exclusive library he/she is paid upfront for the piece but the artist typically sells the publishing rights, hence losing control of the piece and future licensing fees.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Stock footage]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite journal|url=http://www.believermag.com/issues/201207/?read=article_zoladz|last=Zoladz|first=Lindsey|title=Beat Boutique|magazine=[[The Believer (magazine)|The Believer]]|date=July\u2013August 2012}}\n\n* ''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01061hr Into the Library]'', BBC Radio documentary, presenter Jonny Trunk, producer Simon Hollis, Brook Lapping Productions, April 2011\n\n==Further reading==\n* Hollander, David: ''Unusual Sounds: The Hidden History of Library Music''. Anthology, 2018.\n* Lomax, Oliver: ''The Mood Modern: The story of two of the world's greatest recorded music libraries: KPM (1956-1977) and Bruton Music (1978-1980)''. Vocalion, 2018.\n* Trunk, Jonny and Dammers, Jerry: ''The Music Library''. Fuel, 2005, revised and expanded 2016.\n\n[[Category:Production music|*]]\n[[Category:Stock media|Music]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Stock music for film and TV}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=March 2011}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2010}}\n}}\n\n'''Production music''' (also known as '''stock music''' or '''library music''') is the name given to recorded music that can be [[music licensing|licensed]] to customers for use in film, television, radio and other media. Oftentimes, the music is produced and owned by production [[music libraries]].\n\n==Background==\nUnlike popular and classical music publishers, who typically own less than 50 percent of the [[copyright]] in a composition, production music libraries own all of the copyrights of their music. Thus, it can be licensed without the composer's permission, as is necessary in licensing music from normal publishers. This is because virtually all music created for music libraries is done on a [[work for hire]] basis. Production music is a convenient solution for media producers&mdash;they can be assured that they will be able to license any piece of music in the library at a reasonable rate, whereas a specially-commissioned work could be prohibitively expensive. Similarly, licensing a well-known piece of popular music could cost anywhere from tens to hundreds of thousands of dollars, depending on the prominence of the performer(s).\n\nProduction music libraries typically offer a broad range of musical styles and genres, enabling producers and editors to find what they need in the same library. Music libraries vary in size from a few hundred tracks up to many thousands. The first production music library was set up by [[De Wolfe Music]] in 1927 with the advent of sound in film. The company originally scored music for use in silent film.<ref>{{cite book|title=De Wolfe Millennium Catalogue|last=De Wolfe|first=Warren|year=1988|publisher=De Wolfe Music|location=London}}</ref>\n\nProduction music is frequently used as theme and/or background music in radio, film and television. Well-known examples of British TV series whose themes were sourced from library catalogues include ''[[Ski Sunday]]'' (\"Pop Looks Bach\" by Sam Fonteyn), ''[[Dave Allen At Large]]'' (\"Studio 69\" by [[Alan Hawkshaw]]), ''[[Mastermind (TV series)|Mastermind]]'' (\"Approaching Menace\" by [[Neil Richardson (composer)|Neil Richardson]]), the original theme for the BBC's ''[[Grandstand (BBC)|Grandstand]]'' (\"News Scoop\" by Len Stevens), ''[[Crimewatch]]'' (\"Rescue Helicopter\" by [[John Cameron (musician)|John Cameron]]) and ''[[Grange Hill]]'' (\"Chicken Man\" by Alan Hawkshaw). The Christmas hit single based off the character [[Mr Blobby]] uses excerpts from \"Mr Jellybun\" by Paul Shaw and David Rogers. [[Arthur Wood (composer)|Arthur Wood]]'s \"[[Barwick Green]]\", written in 1924, still serves as the theme for long-running BBC Radio soap ''[[The Archers]]''. TV comedy series such as ''[[The Benny Hill Show]]'' and ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'' also made extensive use of production library cues (many sourced from the De Wolfe catalogue)<ref>[http://runstop.de/music07.html William Brown, essay on stock music in ''The Benny Hill Show'']</ref> as background or incidental music.\n\nAmerican TV has also utilized production music, most notably with the themes for ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' (\"[[Heavy Action]]\" by [[Johnny Pearson]]) and ''[[The People's Court]]'' (\"The Big One\" by [[Alan Tew]]). Other notable examples are the [[Nickelodeon (TV channel)|Nickelodeon]] animated series ''[[The Ren and Stimpy Show]]'' and ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'', which use well-known classical music excerpts and a wide range of pre-1960s production music cues\u2014including many pieces familiar from their use in earlier cartoons\u2014which were chosen for their ironic and humorous effect.\n\nProduction music composers and session performers typically work anonymously and have rarely become known outside their professional circle. In recent years some veteran composer-performers in this field such as Alan Hawkshaw, John Cameron and [[Keith Mansfield]] have achieved attention and popularity as a result of a new interest in production music of the 1960s and 1970s, notably the 'beat' and [[electronica]] cues recorded for KPM and other labels, which have been widely sampled by DJs and record producers. In recent years some of these British musicians have given public performances of their classic compositions under the group name [[KPM Allstars]].<ref>[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article666595.ece \"KPM Allstars\", ''The Times'', 10 October 2006]</ref>\n\n==Business model==\nThe business model of production music libraries is based on two income streams:\n\n;License or synchronization fees: These are the fees paid upfront to the library for permission to synchronize its music to a piece of film, video or audio. These fees can range from a few dollars for an internet usage, to thousands for a network commercial usage. Some libraries, especially in the UK and Europe, split these fees with the composer of the music. In the US, it is more common for a composer to be paid a work-for-hire fee upfront by the library for composing the music, thus waiving his/her share of any future license fees. In the UK, license fees for production music are nationally standardized and set by the [[Mechanical-Copyright Protection Society|MCPS]]. In the US and elsewhere, libraries are free to determine their own license fees.\n;Performance income (or performance royalties): Performances income is generated when music is publicly performed - for example, on television or radio. The producer of the show or film that has licensed the music does not pay these fees. Instead, large fees are paid annually by broadcasters (such as television networks and radio stations) to performing rights organizations (PRO's) such as [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP]], [[Broadcast Music Incorporated|BMI]] and [[SESAC]] in the US and the [[PRS for Music|PRS]] in the UK, who then distribute income among their members. To ensure it is distributed fairly and accurately, most broadcasters are required to keep note of what music they have broadcast and for how long. This information is then used by the performance societies to allocate income to their members. Typically, a library will receive 50 percent of the performance income (this is known as the publisher's share), with the composer receiving the remaining 50 percent. Like license fees, performance income is highly variable and dependent on the nature of the usage; local radio usage will yield modest income - perhaps a few dollars each time it is played. Repeated use in a primetime network TV show can generate thousands of dollars. Another method, in the United States, of collecting royalties for performances of production, stock, and library music is through directly negotiating royalties with composers and bypassing PRO's. BMI and ASCAP, and more recently SESAC, no longer have exclusive representation of composers for the collection of performance royalties. By directly negotiating the performance royalties with rights holders, licensees can pay less for the performance of a cue of music, and the licenser (the rights holder) can receive more than the PRO would pay. This is because of the removal of not only the administrative costs incurred through a PRO collecting royalties, but the removal of the \"weight variable\" which pays the highest performing songwriters and composers a portion of all fees collected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvmlc.com/music-licensing/copyright-basics/|title=COPYRIGHT BASICS|work=TVMLC.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.muserk.com/performance-royalties-licenses/|title=Performance Royalties and Licenses|work=Find and license the music you need, fast|access-date=2014-12-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213040503/http://blog.muserk.com/performance-royalties-licenses/|archive-date=2014-12-13|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/creators/royalty/us_television_royalties|title=U.S. Television Royalties|work=BMI.com}}</ref>\n\n== Market ==\nThe production music market is dominated by libraries affiliated with the large record and publishing companies: [[KPM Musichouse|KPM]] is owned by [[EMI]]; [[Universal Music Publishing Group]] library music has the music libraries of Chappell, Bruton, and Atmosphere under their own name as well as others owned by them such as [[Killer Tracks]]; Imagem Production Music (formerly [[Boosey & Hawkes]] Production Music and including the Cavendish, Abaco and Strip Sounds labels) is owned by the Imagem Music Group; [[Extreme Music]] is owned by [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]]; [[BMG Rights Management]] runs its own production music division; and [[Warner/Chappell]] (a division of [[Warner Music Group]]) owns Warner/Chappell Production Music.<ref>{{cite news|title=billboard.com Apr 2012| url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/publishing/1098075/warnerchappel-unites-production-companies-launches-new-website7}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.horizont.net/agenturen/nachrichten/BMG-Production-Music-BMG-gruendet-Agentur-fuer-Produktionsmusik-145935|title=BMG Production Music: BMG gr\u00fcndet Agentur f\u00fcr Produktionsmusik|website=www.horizont.net|language=de|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nEstablished in 1965, [[Sonoton]] is the largest independent production music library in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.professional-production.de/fachbeitraege/einzelansicht/datum/2015/05/31/sonoton-die-ersten-50-jahre/|title=Professional Production - Technologie und Medienrealisation in Film und Video {{!}} Sonoton \u2013 die ersten 50 Jahre|last=Video|first=Professional Production-Technologie und Medienrealisation in Film und|website=www.professional-production.de|language=de|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> There are numerous independent libraries that include [[Vanacore Music]] and [[West One Music Group]].\n\n==Hybrid license method==\nThis method of licensing combines the creation of original, custom music with a catalog of traditional \"library\" music under one license agreement. The goal is to suit the needs of a budget conscious production but still provide that production with a unique and original show theme or audio brand. In this scenario, show producer identifies those scenes she/he feels are most important to the success of the show, and those scenes are scored to picture by the composer. Those less important scenes will utilize the library also provided by the same publisher/composer. Upon completion, the custom music and the library tracks are licensed together under one production blanket, the ownership of the custom music remains with the publisher who produced it, and the publisher can (after a term of exclusivity negotiated between the parties) re-license the custom music as part of its library to recoup production costs.\n\nThis allows the music composer/producer to quote lower rates because they are retaining ownership of the custom music, and will have the ability to make money with the same recording in a different production later on. It also allows the program or film producer to deliver content of very high quality, ensures that the most important scenes have the perfect music, and those less important scenes are addressed with an affordable solution.\n\n==Royalty-free libraries==\nWith the proliferation of music libraries in recent years and the increase in competition, some smaller libraries have evolved the ''royalty-free music'' model. These libraries do not charge their customers for licensing the music. Instead, the customers purchase a CD or access to an electronic collection of music - priced typically between 50 and 300 dollars - whose content is licensed in perpetuity for them to synchronize as often they wish. These libraries depend mainly on performance royalties for their income (with a small amount of income from sales of physical CDs or online track downloads). Assuming that the music is broadcast, royalties are paid on the music, though it is the broadcaster who pays them via annual fees to the performing rights societies, not the producer who uses the music in their production.\n\nSome companies offer truly royalty-free music which is not registered with any [[performance rights organisation]] (also known as \"royalty collection agencies\"). These companies license music to their customers on a non-exclusive basis where it can be used in perpetuity without any usage reporting. The music is licensed by the customers according to an accepted license agreement, and they cannot sell it or license it to others. Because of advancing technology, it is becoming easier for independent musicians to set up their own shops through which they can license music.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thetechreviewer.com/tech-tips/best-royalty-free-music-websites-filmmakers/|title=7 Best Royalty Free Music Websites & Services For Filmmakers|date=2017-08-11|work=TheTechReviewer.com|access-date=2017-08-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Non-exclusive libraries==\nNon-exclusive production music libraries enable a composer to sign a non-exclusive agreement allowing the artist to license the same piece to other libraries and clients with the same non-exclusive agreement. In other words, their intellectual property (their composition) can be licensed to multiple clients simultaneously, provided that they are not contractually bound by an exclusive agreement with another company. The non-exclusive library doesn't own the rights outside of the licenses that are made by that library. Typically the library does not pay for the piece, and the artist doesn't get any payment until the piece is licensed at which point the library and the artist split the license fee equally. Libraries typically require the artist to rename the piece in effect creating a unique artistic work for the library to register with their PRO (BMI, ASCAP, SESAC). Should the composer want to enter the piece into an exclusive agreement with a library or client, they would first need to remove that piece from all non-exclusive agreements.\n\nAn advantage to using a non-exclusive library is the possible broad exposure through multiple outlets, and the ability of the artist to retain control. Conversely, if an artist sells his/her piece to an exclusive library he/she is paid upfront for the piece but the artist typically sells the publishing rights, hence losing control of the piece and future licensing fees.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Stock footage]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite journal|url=http://www.believermag.com/issues/201207/?read=article_zoladz|last=Zoladz|first=Lindsey|title=Beat Boutique|magazine=[[The Believer (magazine)|The Believer]]|date=July\u2013August 2012}}\n\n* ''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01061hr Into the Library]'', BBC Radio documentary, presenter Jonny Trunk, producer Simon Hollis, Brook Lapping Productions, April 2011\n\n==Further reading==\n* Hollander, David: ''Unusual Sounds: The Hidden History of Library Music''. Anthology, 2018.\n* Lomax, Oliver: ''The Mood Modern: The story of two of the world's greatest recorded music libraries: KPM (1956-1977) and Bruton Music (1978-1980)''. Vocalion, 2018.\n* Trunk, Jonny and Dammers, Jerry: ''The Music Library''. Fuel, 2005, revised and expanded 2016.\n\n[[Category:Production music|*]]\n[[Category:Stock media|Music]]\n", "name_user": "Elizabetdeg", "label": "safe", "comment": "change 404 broken link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Production_music"}
{"title_page": "Global Adaptation Network", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe [[United Nations Environment Programme|United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP)]] established the '''Global Adaptation Network''' in 2010 to share and exchange climate change adaptation knowledge across the world1. GAN's secretariat is based at UNEP's Headquarters in Nairobi, Kenya.<ref>{{cite web |title=UNEP Adaptation Networks |url=https://www.unenvironment.org/explore-topics/climate-change/what-we-do/climate-adaptation/knowledge-analysis-and-networking |website=unenvironment.org |publisher=United Nations Environment Programme |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nGAN was formed as an umbrella organization to bring together regional networks across the world that are working on issues related to climate change adaptation. These regional networks include [[Asia Pacific Adaptation Network|Asia Pacific Adaptation Network (APAN)]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Asia Pacific Adaptation Network |url=http://www.asiapacificadapt.net/ |website=asiapacificadapt.net/ |publisher=Asia Pacific Adaptation Network |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> the Regional Gateway for Technology Transfer and Climate Change Action for Latin America and the Caribbean (REGATTA),<ref>{{cite web |title=Regional Gateway for Technology Transfer and Climate Change Action for Latin America and the Caribbean (REGATTA) |url=http://www.cambioclimatico-regatta.org/index.php/en/ |website=REGATTA |publisher=Regional Gateway for Technology Transfer and Climate Change Action for Latin America and the Caribbean (REGATTA) |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>  and Ecosystem-based Adaptation for Food Security in Africa (EBAFOSA).<ref>{{cite web |title=Ecosystem-based Adaptation for Food Security in Africa (EBAFOSA) |url=https://ebafosa.org/ |website=EBAFOSA |publisher=Ecosystem-based Adaptation for Food Security in Africa (EBAFOSA) |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Global Adaptation Network has four main areas of work:<ref>{{cite web |title=WeAdapt |url=https://www.weadapt.org/organisation/gan |website=https://www.weadapt.org/ |publisher=WeAdapt |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Learning Exchanges - \"Sharing adaptation solutions with those who most need them\" ==\n\nThe Global Adaptation Network hosts adaptation Learning Exchanges in regions that are particularly vulnerable to the effects of climate change.<ref>{{cite web |title=US Environment Protection Agency |url=https://www.epa.gov/international-cooperation/epas-role-international-climate-adaptation#GAN |website=https://www.epa.gov |publisher=US Environment Protection Agency |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> Adaptation specialists from different parts of the world come together to share their techniques and expertise in dealing with the challenges borne from increasing weather extremes and the associated effects on livelihoods.<ref>{{cite web |title=Global Adaptation Network (GAN) Brochure |url=https://wedocs.unep.org/bitstream/handle/20.500.11822/25428/Global_adaptation_network.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |website=https://www.unenvironment.org/GAN |publisher=Global Adaptation Network |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFace-to-face Adaptation Learning Exchanges have been held in Honduras, Chile, Mexico, Argentina, South Africa, Mozambique, Malawi, and India.<ref>{{cite web |title=GAN Funds the DAC's Participation at International Events |url=http://www.durbanadaptationcharter.org/news/gan-funds-the-dacs-participation-at-international-events |website=durbanadaptationcharter.org/ |publisher=Durban Adaptation Chapter |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Using university resources to build resilience in cities - \"Connecting university resources to real-world challenges\" ==\n\nThe Global Adaptation Network works closely with the Educational Partnership for Innovation in Communities (EPIC) Network,<ref>{{cite news |title=EPIC Africa training: matching local governments and universities towards more sustainable cities and communities |url=https://start.org/news/epic-africa-training |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=START International |date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> a US-based initiative that connects university resources to real-word challenges in their local cities.<ref>{{cite news |title=EPIC approach to sustainability and climate resilience to expand across Africa |url=https://www.unenvironment.org/news-and-stories/press-release/epic-approach-sustainability-and-climate-resilience-expand-across |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=United Nations Environment Programme |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> The Chronicle of Higher Education called the EPIC model \u201cone of higher education\u2019s most successful and comprehensive service-learning programs.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |title=Livable City Year information for faculty |url=https://www.washington.edu/livable-city-year/faculty/info/ |website=University of Washington |publisher=University of Washington |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> GAN is working with the EPIC Network to extend its model to other parts of the world. Due to this collaboration, an EPIC-Africa network was launched in 2017.\n\n== Global Adaptation Forums - \"Connecting adaptation experts and policymakers into a shared platform\" ==\n\nThe Global Adaptation Network held its last major forum in Abu Dhabi in March 2018,.<ref>{{cite news |title=Global Climate Change Adaptation Experts Revise Best Practices |url=https://www.eyeofriyadh.com/news/details/global-climate-change-adaptation-experts-revise-best-practices |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Eye of Riyadh |publisher=Eye of Riyadh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Climate Change Is Here: Landmark Forum Set To Determine How Humanity Will Adapt |url=https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2018/03/14/climate-change-is-here-landmark-forum-set-to-determine-how-humanity-will-adapt/ |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Modern Diplomacy |publisher=Modern Diplomacy |date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Regional Adaptation Forum Outlines Challenges in Gulf Region, Contributes to Talanoa Dialogue |url=http://sdg.iisd.org/news/regional-adaptation-forum-outlines-challenges-in-gulf-region-contributes-to-talanoa-dialogue/ |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=International Institute of Sustainable Development |publisher=International Institute of Sustainable Development |date=March 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Call for advancement of work in adaptation and resilience at 2nd Global Adaptation Network Forum |url=https://www.adaptationnetwork.org.za/2018/04/call-advancement-work-adaptation-resilience-2nd-global-adaptation-network-forum/ |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=The Adaptation Network |publisher=The Adaptation Network}}</ref> The event explored various themes in adaptation, including how to measure and assess adaptation risks and actions, how to involve the private sector, and how to establish a climate risk insurance scheme in Africa.\n\n== Lima Adaptation Knowledge Initiative (LAKI) - \"Identifying urgent gaps in knowledge and action\" ==\n\nThrough the Lima Adaptation Knowledge Initiative, the Global Adaptation Network works closely with the UNFCCC to identify gaps in adaptation knowledge, as well as formulating guidance for the actions needed to close such gaps.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<br />\n\n[[Category:Climate change organizations]]\n[[Category:United Nations organizations based in Africa]]\n[[Category:United Nations Environment Programme]]\n", "text_old": "The [[United Nations Environment Programme|United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP)]] established the '''Global Adaptation Network''' in 2010 to share and exchange climate change adaptation knowledge across the world1. GAN's secretariat is based at UNEP's Headquarters in Nairobi, Kenya.<ref>{{cite web |title=UNEP Adaptation Networks |url=https://www.unenvironment.org/explore-topics/climate-change/what-we-do/climate-adaptation/knowledge-analysis-and-networking |website=www.unenvironment.org |publisher=United Nations Environment Programme |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nGAN was formed as an umbrella organization to bring together regional networks across the world that are working on issues related to climate change adaptation. These regional networks include [[Asia Pacific Adaptation Network|Asia Pacific Adaptation Network (APAN)]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Asia Pacific Adaptation Network |url=http://www.asiapacificadapt.net/ |website=http://www.asiapacificadapt.net/ |publisher=Asia Pacific Adaptation Network |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> the Regional Gateway for Technology Transfer and Climate Change Action for Latin America and the Caribbean (REGATTA),<ref>{{cite web |title=Regional Gateway for Technology Transfer and Climate Change Action for Latin America and the Caribbean (REGATTA) |url=http://www.cambioclimatico-regatta.org/index.php/en/ |website=REGATTA |publisher=Regional Gateway for Technology Transfer and Climate Change Action for Latin America and the Caribbean (REGATTA) |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>  and Ecosystem-based Adaptation for Food Security in Africa (EBAFOSA).<ref>{{cite web |title=Ecosystem-based Adaptation for Food Security in Africa (EBAFOSA) |url=https://ebafosa.org/ |website=EBAFOSA |publisher=Ecosystem-based Adaptation for Food Security in Africa (EBAFOSA) |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Global Adaptation Network has four main areas of work:<ref>{{cite web |title=WeAdapt |url=https://www.weadapt.org/organisation/gan |website=https://www.weadapt.org/ |publisher=WeAdapt |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Learning Exchanges - \"Sharing adaptation solutions with those who most need them\" ==\n\nThe Global Adaptation Network hosts adaptation Learning Exchanges in regions that are particularly vulnerable to the effects of climate change.<ref>{{cite web |title=US Environment Protection Agency |url=https://www.epa.gov/international-cooperation/epas-role-international-climate-adaptation#GAN |website=https://www.epa.gov |publisher=US Environment Protection Agency |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> Adaptation specialists from different parts of the world come together to share their techniques and expertise in dealing with the challenges borne from increasing weather extremes and the associated effects on livelihoods.<ref>{{cite web |title=Global Adaptation Network (GAN) Brochure |url=https://wedocs.unep.org/bitstream/handle/20.500.11822/25428/Global_adaptation_network.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |website=https://www.unenvironment.org/GAN |publisher=Global Adaptation Network |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFace-to-face Adaptation Learning Exchanges have been held in Honduras, Chile, Mexico, Argentina, South Africa, Mozambique, Malawi, and India.<ref>{{cite web |title=GAN Funds the DAC's Participation at International Events |url=http://www.durbanadaptationcharter.org/news/gan-funds-the-dacs-participation-at-international-events |website=http://www.durbanadaptationcharter.org/ |publisher=Durban Adaptation Chapter |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Using university resources to build resilience in cities - \"Connecting university resources to real-world challenges\" ==\n\nThe Global Adaptation Network works closely with the Educational Partnership for Innovation in Communities (EPIC) Network,<ref>{{cite news |title=EPIC Africa training: matching local governments and universities towards more sustainable cities and communities |url=https://start.org/news/epic-africa-training |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=START International |date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> a US-based initiative that connects university resources to real-word challenges in their local cities.<ref>{{cite news |title=EPIC approach to sustainability and climate resilience to expand across Africa |url=https://www.unenvironment.org/news-and-stories/press-release/epic-approach-sustainability-and-climate-resilience-expand-across |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=United Nations Environment Programme |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> The Chronicle of Higher Education called the EPIC model \u201cone of higher education\u2019s most successful and comprehensive service-learning programs.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |title=Livable City Year information for faculty |url=https://www.washington.edu/livable-city-year/faculty/info/ |website=University of Washington |publisher=University of Washington |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> GAN is working with the EPIC Network to extend its model to other parts of the world. Due to this collaboration, an EPIC-Africa network was launched in 2017.\n\n== Global Adaptation Forums - \"Connecting adaptation experts and policymakers into a shared platform\" ==\n\nThe Global Adaptation Network held its last major forum in Abu Dhabi in March 2018,.<ref>{{cite news |title=Global Climate Change Adaptation Experts Revise Best Practices |url=https://www.eyeofriyadh.com/news/details/global-climate-change-adaptation-experts-revise-best-practices |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Eye of Riyadh |publisher=Eye of Riyadh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Climate Change Is Here: Landmark Forum Set To Determine How Humanity Will Adapt |url=https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2018/03/14/climate-change-is-here-landmark-forum-set-to-determine-how-humanity-will-adapt/ |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Modern Diplomacy |publisher=Modern Diplomacy |date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Regional Adaptation Forum Outlines Challenges in Gulf Region, Contributes to Talanoa Dialogue |url=http://sdg.iisd.org/news/regional-adaptation-forum-outlines-challenges-in-gulf-region-contributes-to-talanoa-dialogue/ |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=International Institute of Sustainable Development |publisher=International Institute of Sustainable Development |date=March 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Call for advancement of work in adaptation and resilience at 2nd Global Adaptation Network Forum |url=https://www.adaptationnetwork.org.za/2018/04/call-advancement-work-adaptation-resilience-2nd-global-adaptation-network-forum/ |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=The Adaptation Network |publisher=The Adaptation Network}}</ref> The event explored various themes in adaptation, including how to measure and assess adaptation risks and actions, how to involve the private sector, and how to establish a climate risk insurance scheme in Africa.\n\n== Lima Adaptation Knowledge Initiative (LAKI) - \"Identifying urgent gaps in knowledge and action\" ==\n\nThrough the Lima Adaptation Knowledge Initiative, the Global Adaptation Network works closely with the UNFCCC to identify gaps in adaptation knowledge, as well as formulating guidance for the actions needed to close such gaps.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<br />\n[[Category:Climate change organizations]]\n[[Category:United Nations organizations based in Africa]]\n[[Category:United Nations Environment Programme]]\n", "name_user": "Kahtar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair CS1 error(s), replaced: website=http://www. \u2192 website= (2), website=www. \u2192 website=, addedunderlinkedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_Adaptation_Network"}
{"title_page": "Aiviq", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= Aiviq 30dec2012.jpg\n|Ship image size = 300px\n|Ship caption = ''Aiviq'' in heavy seas on 30 December 2012.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[United States]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United States|government}}\n| Ship name=''Aiviq''\n| Ship namesake=[[Inupiaq language|Inupiaq]] for \"[[walrus]]\"\n| Ship owner=[[Edison Chouest Offshore]]\n| Ship operator=\n| Ship registry=[[Galliano, Louisiana|Galliano]], [[Louisiana]], {{USA}}<ref name=\"abs\" />\n| Ship route=\n| Ship ordered=July 2009\n| Ship builder=*[[North American Shipbuilding]], [[Larose, Louisiana]]\n*[[LaShip]], [[Houma, Louisiana]]\n| Ship original cost=$200 million\n| Ship yard number=247\n| Ship way number=\n| Ship laid down=3 February 2010\n| Ship launched=1 November 2011\n| Ship christened=24 March 2012\n| Ship completed=20 April 2012\n| Ship acquired=\n| Ship maiden voyage=\n| Ship in service=2012\u2013\n| Ship out of service=\n| Ship identification=*{{IMO number|9579016}}\n*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: WDG2524\n*{{MMSI|367141000}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9579016|shipname=Aiviq|accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref>\n| Ship fate=\n| Ship status=In service<ref name=\"equasis\" />\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship class=\n| Ship type=[[Anchor handling tug supply vessel]] (AHTS)\n| Ship tonnage=*{{GT|12,892}}\n*{{NetT|3,867}}\n*{{DWT|4,129}}\n| Ship displacement=\n| Ship length={{convert|110|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam={{convert|24.4|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height=\n| Ship draught={{convert|8.6|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth={{convert|10.4|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship ice class=[[American Bureau of Shipping|ABS]] A3\n| Ship power=4{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar]] C280-12 (4{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}4,060{{nbsp}}kW)\n| Ship propulsion=*Two [[Ducted propeller|ducted]] [[controllable-pitch propeller]]s\n*Three [[bow thruster]]s and two stern thrusters\n| Ship speed=*{{convert|15|kn}} in open water\n*{{convert|5|kn}} in {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on}} ice\n| Ship capacity=\n| Ship crew=28; accommodation for 64\n| Ship aircraft facilities = Helideck\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Aiviq''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[icebreaker|icebreaking]] [[anchor handling tug supply vessel]] (AHTS) owned by [[Edison Chouest Offshore]] (ECO). The $200 million vessel was built in 2012 by [[North American Shipbuilding]] in [[Larose, Louisiana]] and LaShip in [[Houma, Louisiana]]. She has been chartered by [[Royal Dutch Shell]] to support oil exploration and drilling in the [[Chukchi Sea]] off [[Alaska]].<ref name=\"workboat\" /> The primary task of the vessel is towing and laying anchors for drilling rigs, but she is also equipped for [[Oil spill#Cleanup and recovery|oil spill response]].<ref name=AnchorageDailyNews2011-12-06>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.adn.com/2011/12/05/2204274/shell-about-to-unveil-200-million.html \n |title=Shell to unveil icebreaker for Arctic Alaska offshore drilling: Vessel will work waters off Alaska during oil exploration \n |publisher=[[Anchorage Daily News]] \n |date=2011-12-06 \n |accessdate=2012-01-26 \n |author=Lisa Demer \n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107133034/http://www.adn.com/2011/12/05/2204274/shell-about-to-unveil-200-million.html\n |archivedate=2012-01-07\n}} ()\n</ref><ref name=MarineLink2012-01-17>{{cite news|url=http://www.marinelink.com/news/exploration-icebreaker342119.aspx |title=Shell Awaits New Giant Icebreaker |publisher=[[Marinelink]] |date=2012-01-17 |accessdate=2012-01-26 |author=Susan Buchanan |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127101801/http://www.marinelink.com/news/exploration-icebreaker342119.aspx |archivedate=2012-01-27 }} ()</ref>\n\nThe vessel has been called the world's most powerful privately owned icebreaker.<ref name=maritimeExecutive2018-01-02/>\n\n==Construction==\n\nIn July 2009, Edison Chouest Offshore won a $150 million contract for the construction of an icebreaking anchor handling tug supply (AHTS) vessel for [[Royal Dutch Shell]]. The {{convert|360|ft|m|adj=on}} vessel, largest ever built by the company, would be used to support Shell's drilling operations in the [[Beaufort Sea]] and [[Chukchi Sea]] off [[Alaska]].<ref>[http://www.dailycomet.com/article/20090722/HURBLOG/907229884/1223?Title=Chouest-scores-new-icebreaker-contract Chouest scores new icebreaker contract]. dailycomet.com, 22 July 2009. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> In January 2010, it was announced that the  vessel would be constructed in [[Louisiana]]. The hull and the superstructure would be built in the company's own shipyard [[North American Shipbuilding]] in [[Larose, Louisiana|Larose]] in two separate units while the final assembly of the vessel would take place at LaShip, also owned by Edison Chouest, in [[Houma, Louisiana|Houma]]. In all, the construction would take just over two years and provide work for about 800 people.<ref>[http://www.dailycomet.com/article/20100122/ARTICLES/100129748 Icebreaker to be built locally]. dailycomet.com, 22 January 2010. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n\n[[Keel laying|Laid down]] on 3 February 2010,<ref name=\"abs\" /> the newbuilding \"Hull 247\" was presented to Shell executives on 30 September 2011. By then, the price of the vessel had climbed to $200 million due to material and equipment factors, such as the price of steel.<ref>[http://www.wwltv.com/news/Shell-execs-get-glimpse-of-all-new-icebreaker-ship-design-130914038.html Shell execs get glimpse of 'all new' icebreaker ship design] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808041748/http://www.wwltv.com/news/Shell-execs-get-glimpse-of-all-new-icebreaker-ship-design-130914038.html |date=2014-08-08 }}. WWLTV, 1 October 2011. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref><ref>[http://www.chron.com/business/article/Shell-hopes-to-break-the-ice-on-Arctic-drilling-2197495.php Shell hopes to break the ice on Arctic drilling]. Chron, 30 September 2011. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> The vessel was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 1 November 2011.<ref name=\"abs\" /> According to Edison Chouest spokesman Gary Chouest, ''\"It [''Aiviq''] will be the world's largest and most powerful anchor-handling icebreaker.\"''<ref name=AnchorageDailyNews2011-12-06/>\n\nIn 2011, Shell invited [[Inupiak]] schoolchildren to submit essays suggesting names for the vessel. Twelve-year-old Elizabeth Itta submitted the winning essay, describing how the [[Walrus]], \"Aiviq\" in the Inupiak language, use their tusks to break ice. She won a cash prize for her school and an invitation to attend the ship's launching ceremony on 24 March 2012.<ref name=Shell>{{cite news|url=http://www.shell.us/home/content/usa/aboutshell/projects_locations/alaska/events_news/12092012_walrus.html |title=Winner of Ice Breaker Naming Contest |publisher=[[Shell Oil]] |date=2011-12-09 |accessdate=2012-01-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514135634/http://www.shell.us/home/content/usa/aboutshell/projects_locations/alaska/events_news/12092012_walrus.html |archivedate=2012-05-14 }} ()</ref><ref>[http://shipbuildingtribune.com/2012/03/26/usa-edison-chouest-offshore-shipyard-christens-shells-new-icebreaker-aiviq/ USA: Edison Chouest Offshore Shipyard Christens Shell\u2019s New Icebreaker Aiviq] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712122557/http://shipbuildingtribune.com/2012/03/26/usa-edison-chouest-offshore-shipyard-christens-shells-new-icebreaker-aiviq/ |date=2012-07-12 }}. ShipbuildingTribune.com, 26 March 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> The vessel went for sea trials in April and was delivered on 20 April 2012.<ref name=\"abs\" /><ref name=\"marinelog1april\">[http://www.marinelog.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2208 Giant ice-class AHTS on sea trials following completion by Chouest] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214072026/http://www.marinelog.com/index.php?option=com_content |date=2012-02-14 }}. MarineLog, 1 April 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe construction of the new icebreaker and Shell's Arctic drilling operation off Alaska raised concerns about the ability of the [[United States Coast Guard]] to operate in ice-infested waters since at the time the Coast Guard had only one operational icebreaker, {{USCGC|Healy}}.<ref>[http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-07-18/shell-led-arctic-push-finds-u-dot-s-dot-shy-in-icebreakers-energy Shell-Led Arctic Push Finds U.S. Shy in Icebreakers: Energy]. [[Bloomberg BusinessWeek]], 18 July 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, it was reported that Edison Chouest would build two [[Polar Class 3]] anchor-handling tug supply (AHTS) vessels at the company's LaShip shipyard in Houma, Louisiana. Unlike ''Aiviq'', the new vessels would have been fitted with [[Rolls-Royce Holdings|Rolls-Royce]] [[azimuth thruster]]s instead of conventional shaftlines and rudders.<ref>[http://www.rolls-royce.com/media/press-releases/yr-2015/pr-040315-rr-to-supply-propulsion-and-deck.aspx Rolls-Royce to supply propulsion and deck machinery to a new vessel for Edison Chouest]. Rolls-Royce, 4 March 2015. {{retrieved|accessdate=2016-05-14}}</ref> However, in November 2015 it was reported that Edison Chouest might have canceled the vessels following Shell's decision to halt Arctic oil exploration.<ref>[http://www.marinelog.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=10031:chouest-said-to-have-canceled-arctic-ahts-duo&Itemid=230 Chouest said to have canceled Arctic AHTS duo]. MarineLog, 9 November 2015. {{retrieved|\u0259ccessdate=2016-05-14}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n{{expand section|date=January 2013}}\n\n=== Grounding of ''Kulluk'' ===\n[[File:KullukAground 1jan2013.JPG|thumb|left|''Kulluk'' aground on the southeast side of Sitkalidak Island, Alaska, on 1 January 2013.]]\nOn 27 December 2012, while ''Aiviq'' was towing the mobile offshore drilling unit ''[[Kulluk]]'' off the coast of [[Kodiak Island]], [[Alaska]], the towing line between the icebreaker and the drilling rig parted due to a mechanical failure of the towing shackle.<ref name=\"sitrep\">[http://dec.alaska.gov/spar/perp/response/sum_fy13/121227201/121227201_sr_02.pdf M/V Aiviq Tow-Gulf of Alaska]. Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation, 28 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref> Shortly after the tow had been regained, the main engines of ''Aiviq'' failed and the vessel lost propulsion power in {{convert|20|ft|m|0|adj=on}} seas. In the following morning, power was successfully restored on one of the four main engines and the vessel was able to hold position in the heavy weather.<ref name=\"aiviq1\">[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1669855/MV-Aiviq-loses-power-at-sea MV Aiviq loses power at sea]. Aiviq Tow - Gulf of Alaska, Unified Command, 28 December 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-12-28}}</ref> [[United States Coast Guard]] cutter [[USCGC Alex Haley (WMEC-39)|USCGC ''Alex Haley'']] was dispatched to the scene to monitor the situation.<ref>[http://d17.uscgnews.com/go/doc/4007/1669275/ Coast Guard assists tug and tow in Gulf of Alaska] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102220503/http://d17.uscgnews.com/go/doc/4007/1669275/ |date=2013-01-02 }}. United States Coast Guard, 28 December 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> In response to the incident, the Coast Guard, Shell and Edison Chouest established a Unified Command to coordinate the operation.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1669883/Unified-Command-established Unified Command established]. Unified Command, 28 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> Shell-contracted vessels [[MV Guardsman|''Guardsman'']] and [[MV Nanuq|''Nanuq'']] were also en route to the scene.<ref name=\"aiviq1\" />\n\nOn 29 December, the Unified Command authorized the drilling rig to drop its anchor to slow its drift towards the coast and ordered the Coast Guard to evacuate the 18 crew members on ''Kulluk'' by helicopter as a precaution.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1669911/Unified-Command-Statement-3 Unified Command Statement #3]. Unified Command, 29 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref><ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1669915/Unified-Command-authorizes-Kulluk-to-drop-anchor-to-slow-drift Unified Command authorizes Kulluk to drop anchor to slow drift]. Unified Command, 29 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> [[Sikorsky HH-60 Jayhawk]] helicopters operated by the Coast Guard also delivered essential equipment parts to ''Aiviq'' and later power was restored on all four engines. Together with ''Nanuq'', ''Aiviq'' was able to hold the drilling rig stationary during the crew evacuation and later continue towing the vessel away from the coast.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1669919/Incident-response-continues-second-engine-running-on-Aiviq- Incident response continues, second engine running on Aiviq]. Unified Command, 29 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref><ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670119/Update-6-18-personnel-on-Kulluk-safely-evacuated-Aiviq-s-4-engines-functioning Update #6: 18 personnel on Kulluk safely evacuated, Aiviq\u2019s 4 engines functioning]. Unified Command, 29 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 December, the tow lines of ''Aiviq'' and ''Nanuq'' parted again, and ''Kulluk'' began drifting towards the coast. Another tugboat, the 10,000-horsepower [[MV Alert|''Alert'']] operated by [[Crowley Maritime|Crowley Marine Services]],<ref>[http://www.tugboatinformation.com/tug.cfm?id=1176 Alert]. Tugboat-information.com. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> also arrived to the scene from [[Prince William Sound]].<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670283/Update-9-Kulluk-tow-lines-separated-Alert-on-scene Update #9: Kulluk tow lines separated; Alert on scene]. Unified Command, 30 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> Shortly after midnight, ''Alert'' was able to secure connection to the {{convert|400|ft|m|adj=on}} towing line previously used by ''Aiviq'' and later in the morning the icebreaker had also reconnected to ''Kulluk'' about {{convert|19|nmi}} southeast from Kodiak Island.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670343/Update-10-Kulluk-under-tow-by-Aiviq-and-Alert Update #10: Kulluk under tow by Aiviq and Alert]. Unified Command, 31 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> USCGC ''Alex Haley'' also returned to the scene from Kodiak, where the cutter had repaired her fouled port propeller, and relieved the crew of [[USCGC Spar (WLB-206)|USCGC ''Spar'']] as on scene commander. The helicopter crews were also preparing to deploy several technicians aboard the drilling rig to evaluate the condition of the towing lines.<ref name=\"uscg1\">[http://www.uscgnews.com/go/doc/4007/1670651/ Coast Guard crews continue battling fierce storm to assist Kulluk near Kodiak, Alaska] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105174055/http://www.uscgnews.com/go/doc/4007/1670651/ |date=2013-01-05 }}. United States Coast Guard, 31 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n\nLater in the evening, ''Kulluk'' was again set adrift after the Coast Guard ordered ''Alert'' to separate from the rig, now only {{convert|4|nmi}} from the nearest point of land, to maintain the safety of the nine crew members on board the tug in nearly {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=on}} seas.<ref name=\"uscg1\" /><ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670671/Update-11-Kulluk-is-adrift-four-miles-from-nearest-point-of-land Kulluk is adrift; four miles from nearest point of land]. Unified Command, 31 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> Only moments later, ''Kulluk'' was grounded near the uninhabited [[Sitkalidak Island]] at a depth of about {{convert|32|-|48|ft|m}}.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670687/Unified-Command-Update-12-Kulluk-grounded-vessel-condition-not-yet-confirmed Unified Command Update #12: Kulluk grounded, vessel condition not yet confirmed]. Unified Command, 31 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n\nThe salvage operation was awarded to the Dutch [[marine salvage|salvage company]] [[Smit International]].<ref name=\"salvage\">[http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1671847/CORRECTION-Update-18-Salvage-Assessment-Team-Safely-Boards-Drilling-Unit Update #18: Salvage Assessment Team Safely Boards Drilling Unit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106030624/http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1671847/CORRECTION-Update-18-Salvage-Assessment-Team-Safely-Boards-Drilling-Unit |date=2013-01-06 }}. Unified Command, 2 January 2013. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-04}}</ref> A team of five salvage experts boarded ''Kulluk'' on 2 January 2013 to assess the structural integrity of the grounded drilling barge.<ref name=\"salvage\" /> On 3 January, it was reported that ''Kulluk'' had suffered damage since the grounding but its structural integrity had not been compromised and there have been no leaks from the rig's fuel tanks.<ref>[http://www.ktuu.com/news/kulluk-has-suffered-damage-since-grounding-hasnt-leaked-oil-010312,0,5074823.story Kulluk Has Suffered Damage Since Grounding, Hasn't Leaked Oil] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107211903/http://www.ktuu.com/news/kulluk-has-suffered-damage-since-grounding-hasnt-leaked-oil-010312,0,5074823.story |date=2013-01-07 }}. KTUU.com, 3 January 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-04}}</ref> At the time of the grounding, ''Kulluk'' was carrying 139,000 gallons of diesel fuel and 12,000 gallons of lubricating and hydraulic oil.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670699/Unified-Command-Update-13 Unified Command Update #13]. Unified Command, 1 January 2013. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> By 4 January, 14 vessels had been mobilized for the recovery operation and the [[United States Department of Defense]] provided two [[Boeing CH-47 Chinook]] helicopters to transport heavy salvage gear to the site.<ref>[http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1674171/ Update #21: Extensive Air and Sea Activity as Kulluk Recovery Operations Continue] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20130216085225/http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1674171/ |date=2013-02-16 }}. Unified Command, 4 January 2013. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref>\n\n''Kulluk'' was successfully refloated on 6 January and towed to a sheltered location in [[Kiliuda Bay]], some {{convert|30|nmi}} from the original grounding location, on the following day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Grounded Shell oil-drilling ship refloated|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/grounded-shell-oil-drilling-ship-refloated|publisher=The Associated Press|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1675595/#.UOs5H3h9SHd Update #34: Kulluk arrives safely at Kiliuda Bay, will undergo assessment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111013208/http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1675595#.UOs5H3h9SHd |date=2013-01-11 }}. Unified Command, 7 January 2013. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-07}}</ref> After the rig was brought to a shipyard in [[Singapore]] on board a heavy-lift vessel, Shell decided not to repair the damages and sold the drilling unit for recycling in China.<ref>[http://www.petroleumnews.com/pntruncate/81694360.shtml Shell responds to BOEM]. Petroleum News, 5 January 2014. {{retrieved|accessdate=2014-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn the investigation report published by the United States Coast Guard on 2 April 2014, the initiating event to the casualty was identified as the failure of a 120-ton apex [[shackle]] which was considered undersized for towing ''Kulluk'' in such environmental conditions. The 90-feet [[Catenary#Anchoring of marine objects|catenary]] surge chain used to damp shock loads in the towing line was also deemed insufficient. According to the Coast Guard, the \"numerous and compounding preconditions\" that led to the casualty also included various operational issues such as the towing plans that were not adequate for the winter towing operation crossing the Gulf of Alaska and the crew's lack of towing experience in the Gulf of Alaska waters particularly during the wintertime.<ref name=\"accidentreport\">[https://www.dco.uscg.mil/Portals/9/DCO%20Documents/5p/CG-5PC/INV/docs/documents/Kulluk.pdf Report of Investigation into the Circumstances Surrounding the Multiple Related Marine Casualties and Grounding of the MODU KULLUK on December 31, 2012]. United States Coast Guard, 2 April 2014. {{retrieved|accessdate=2018-10-31}}</ref>\n\nIn the same report, it was also concluded that the likely cause for ''Aiviq''{{'}}s loss of main engine power was sea water in the fuel oil. After the casualty, sea water contamination was found in settling tanks, day tanks, main engine primary filters and main engine injectors. The design of the vessel allowed considerable amount of sea water to enter the stern deck and subsequently to the fuel oil tanks through overflow vents in heavy weather. There were also problems with fuel management practices onboard ''Aiviq''.<ref name=\"accidentreport\" />\n\n''Kulluk'''s movement south for the winter was at least in part motivated by an effort to avoid State of Alaska property taxes on oil and gas extraction equipment.<ref name=\"dispatch-ben\">{{Cite news | work = [[Alaska Dispatch]] | title = Did Alaska tax liability influence Shell Oil's latest Arctic fiasco? | url = http://www.alaskadispatch.com/article/did-alaska-tax-liability-influence-shell-oils-latest-arctic-fiasco | first = Ben | last = Anderson | date = {{date|2013-01-03|mdy}} | accessdate = {{date|2011-11-15|mdy}}}}</ref>\n\n===Proposed sale to US Coast Guard===\nOn 14 May 2015, [[US Congressman]] [[Duncan D. Hunter|Duncan Hunter]] of California, began advocating for the acquisition of ''Aiviq'' by the [[US Coast Guard]] (USCG) due to an availability gap caused by USCG's retirement of the icebreaker [[USCGC Healy (WAGB-20)|USCGC ''Healy'']].<ref name=\"SDUT Hunter\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=[Coast Guard Adm. Charles] Michel said the Coast Guard\u2019s commandant had personally visited the vessel and found it \"not suitable for military service without substantial refit.\" He said the Coast Guard does not operate non-military icebreakers.}}</ref> USCG repeatedly turned down Hunter's continued proposals, citing the vessel's unsuitability for military operations and being less-capable than ''Healy'', with Coast Guard Admiral [[Charles D. Michel|Charles Michel]] stating ''Aiviq'' is \"Not suitable for military service without substantial refit. [...] We have very specific requirements for our vessels, including international law requirements for assertion of things like navigation rights. This vessel does not just break ice.\"<ref name=\"SDUT Hunter\" /><ref name=\"MAREX\">{{cite web|title=Rep. Young Pushes Coast Guard to Consider the Aiviq|url=https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/rep-young-pushes-coast-guard-to-consider-the-aiviq|publisher=The Maritime Executive|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122094801/https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/rep-young-pushes-coast-guard-to-consider-the-aiviq|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 July 2016|quote=Without modification, the Aiviq is somewhat less capable than the Coast Guard medium icebreaker Healy, and is not in the same class as the heavy icebreaker due to retire next decade, the Polar Star.}}</ref>\n\nControversy arose after it was published that Congressman Hunter had received campaign funding from ''Aiviq''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s owner, [[Edison Chouest Offshore]], and contributors connected to the owner, six days before initially advocating the vessel's sale to USCG.<ref name=\"SDUT Hunter 2\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=The Chouest funds were all received May 8, 2015 \u2014 six days before the Coast Guard was to have an acquisitions hearing before a Congressional subcommittee chaired by Hunter.}}</ref> Edison Chouest's contributions to Hunter have made them the congressman's second largest donor.<ref name=\"SDUT Hunter 3\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=Contributors connected to the Aiviq\u2019s owner, Louisiana-based shipbuilder Edison Chouest Offshore, have given at least $18,000 to Hunter\u2019s campaign since January 2015. That\u2019s a fraction of the $911,000 that Hunter raised during that time period. It makes Chouest the second most generous supporter of Hunter, according to review by The San Diego Union-Tribune of campaign finance records.}}</ref> The company's donations came as Congressman Hunter was under investigation for misuse of campaign funds.<ref name=\"SDUT Hunter 4\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=The money entered Hunter\u2019s campaign coffers at the height of a problem he has since acknowledged with thousands of dollars of campaign funds that were spent on personal expenses \u2014 such as $1,137 for oral surgery the following month.}}</ref> On 12 July 2016, Hunter's advocacy for the vessel's acquisition was joined by US Congressman [[Don Young]] of Alaska.<ref name=\"SDUT Young\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=At the subcommittee hearing July 12, Hunter had an ally in Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, who also believes the Coast Guard does not require military-grade vessels for ice breaking. He described Michel\u2019s justification for not wanting to lease the Aiviq because it\u2019s not a military vessel as \u201ca bulls--- answer.\u201d Since 2015, Edison Chouest Offshore was Young\u2019s top campaign contributor, donating at least $28,300, according to Opensecrets.org.}}</ref> ''Aiviq''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s owner was Congressman Young's largest campaign donor at that time.<ref name=\"Young contribs\">{{cite web|title=Rep. Don Young - Alaska District 01 - Contributors 2015 - 2016|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/members-of-congress/contributors?cid=N00007999&cycle=2016|website=[[OpenSecrets]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122100139/https://www.opensecrets.org/members-of-congress/contributors?cid=N00007999&cycle=2016|archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nCongressman Hunter's office estimated it would cost US$33 million a year to lease, or US$150 million to buy ''Aiviq'' outright.<ref name=\"Def News\">{{cite web|author1=Joe Gould|title=US Lawmaker Wants Pre-Owned Ice Ship Over Coast Guard Objections|url=https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2016/09/30/us-lawmaker-wants-pre-owned-ice-ship-over-coast-guard-objections/|website=[[Defense News]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180122102528/https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2016/09/30/us-lawmaker-wants-pre-owned-ice-ship-over-coast-guard-objections/|archivedate=2018-01-22|date=30 September 2016|quote=Hunter claims the cost to charter an existing vessel, called the Aiviq, would be $33 million per year to lease and $150 million to buy.|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"SDUT Hunter 5\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=Last month, Hunter asked Republican House leadership for money to be included in \u201cany suitable and forthcoming appropriations vehicle\u201d for lease or purchase of a medium icebreaker, according to a Sept. 20 letter Hunter\u2019s office released to the Union-Tribune on Thursday. The letter estimated the costs to charter the Aiviq at $33 million per year to lease, or $150 million to buy.}}</ref>\n\n=== Proposed sale to Canada ===\n\nSince 2016, [[Davie Shipbuilding]] has offered ''Aiviq'' together with other out-of-work offshore icebreakers to the [[Canadian Coast Guard]] as a replacement for {{ship|CCGS|Louis S. St-Laurent}}.<ref>[http://www.davie.ca/pdf/Aiviq.pdf Aiviq - Polar Icebreaker]. Davie Shipbuilding. {{retrieved|accessdate=2016-06-13}}</ref> However, recent reports indicate that the Canadian Coast Guard is not interested in the vessel.<ref>[http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1091392/brise-glaces-davie Brise-glaces et Davie : des doutes sur la volont\u00e9 d\u2019Ottawa]. Radio-Canada, 26 March 2018. {{retrieved|accessdate=2018-03-28}}</ref> In June 2018, it was announced that the Canadian government ended up partnering with Davie Shipbuilding, but using three ships from [[Viking Supply Ships]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.marinelog.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=29600:canada-taps-davie-for-three-ahts-conversion-medium-icebreakers&Itemid=231 | title = Canada taps Davie for three AHTS-conversion medium icebreakers | date = 2018-06-22 | work = Marine Log | publisher = Simmons-Boardman Publishing}}</ref>\n\n==General characteristics==\n''Aiviq'' is {{convert|110|m|ftin}} [[length overall|long overall]] and {{convert|95.5|m|ftin}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]]. Her hull has a beam of {{convert|24.4|m|ft}} and depth of {{convert|10.4|m|ftin}}.<ref name=\"abs\">{{csr|register=ABS|id=12185769|shipname=Aiviq|accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref> Fully laden, she draws {{convert|8.6|m|ftin}} of water.<ref name=\"shell\">[http://www.shell.us/home/content/usa/aboutshell/projects_locations/alaska/events_news/03262012_ice-vessel.html Shell Takes Delivery of New Ice Class Vessel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514141647/http://www.shell.us/home/content/usa/aboutshell/projects_locations/alaska/events_news/03262012_ice-vessel.html |date=2012-05-14 }}. Shell, 24 March 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref> Since ''Aiviq'' is an anchor handling tug and supply vessel, she is fitted with a large towing winch located amidships as well as chain lockers and storage tanks for both liquid and dry bulk cargo under the main deck.<ref name=\"ga\">[http://www.boem.gov/uploadedFiles/BOEM/Oil_and_Gas_Energy_Program/Plans/Regional_Plans/Alaska_Exploration_Plans/2012_Shell_Beaufort_EP/Appendix%20K%20-%20Ice%20Management.pdf Appendix K: Ice management plan]. Shell Offshore Inc. Pages 41\u201343. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref> Her [[gross tonnage]] is 12,892, [[net tonnage]] 3,867 and [[deadweight tonnage]] 4,129 tonnes.<ref name=\"abs\" />\n\n''Aiviq'' is powered by four [[V12 engine|12-cylinder]] [[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar]] C280-12 [[Four-stroke engine|four stroke]] medium speed [[diesel engine]]s, each producing {{convert|4060|kW|hp|abbr=on}} at 1,000 rpm. The engines are coupled to two {{convert|4.6|m|ft|adj=on}} [[Schottel (company)|Schottel]] [[controllable-pitch propeller]] in [[Ducted propeller|nozzles]] via [[Flender]] reduction gearboxes.<ref name=\"abs\" /><ref name=\"pride\">[http://www.professionalmariner.com/American-Ship-Review-2013/Aiviq-Pride-of-Shells-Alaskan-drilling-fleet/ Aiviq: Pride of Shell\u2019s Alaskan drilling fleet]. Professional Mariner, 16 October 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> The propulsion system gives ''Aiviq'' a service speed of {{convert|15|kn}} in open water and {{convert|5|kn}} in {{convert|1|m|ftin|adj=on}} level ice, and a bollard pull of 200 metric tons.<ref name=\"shell\" /> She also has two 2,000&nbsp;kW shaft generators and four 1,700&nbsp;kW Caterpillar 3512C auxiliary diesel generators that provide power for onboard consumers, including the firefighting system. She has three [[bow thruster]]s, one of them of [[azimuth thruster|azimuthing]] fold-down type, and two stern thrusters that give her [[dynamic positioning]] capability. For redundancy and improved handling, she has two high-lift rudders.<ref name=\"abs\" /><ref name=\"workboat\">[http://www.workboat.com/newsdetail.aspx?id=13632 Breaking the Ice] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231203222/http://www.workboat.com/newsdetail.aspx?id=13632 |date=2014-12-31 }}. WorkBoat.com, 15 May 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref><ref name=\"ga\" /> The propellers of ''Aiviq'' are reportedly designed to be quieter than normal in order to be less disruptive to local marine life.<ref name=Ktuu2011-11-14>{{cite news|url=http://articles.ktuu.com/2011-11-14/arctic-offshore-drilling_30399477 |title=Shell Offshore: Arctic Icebreaker Takes Shape |publisher=[[KTUU]] |date=2011-11-14 |accessdate=2012-01-27 |author=Ted Land |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119010412/http://articles.ktuu.com/2011-11-14/arctic-offshore-drilling_30399477 |archivedate=2012-01-19 }}</ref>\n\n''Aiviq'' is classified by the [[American Bureau of Shipping]]. Her ice class, ABS A3, indicates that she is strengthened for navigation in polar ice conditions with the presence of multiyear ice floes. Furthermore, the notation \"Ice Breaker\" states that she is designed and constructed for breaking ice to open navigable channels for other ships.<ref name=\"abs\" /><ref name=\"MAREX\" />\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat|IMO 9579016|''Aiviq''}}\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=maritimeExecutive2018-01-02>\n{{cite news \n| url         = https://www.maritime-executive.com/editorials/an-out-of-the-blue-icebreaker-opportunity\n| title       = An Out-of-the-Blue Icebreaker Opportunity\n| work        = [[Maritime Executive]]\n| author      = [[Pierre LeBlanc]]\n| date        = 2018-01-02\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20180107085857/https://www.maritime-executive.com/editorials/an-out-of-the-blue-icebreaker-opportunity\n| archivedate = 2018-01-07\n| accessdate  = 2018-11-28\n| url-status     = live \n| quote       = The m/v Aiviq is a Polar Class 3 icebreaker built by North American Shipbuilders in 2012. It is reported to be the world\u2019s most powerful icebreaker privately owned.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Category:2011 ships]]\n[[Category:Icebreakers of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= Aiviq 30dec2012.jpg\n|Ship image size = 300px\n|Ship caption = ''Aiviq'' in heavy seas on 30 December 2012.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[United States]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United States|government}}\n| Ship name=''Aiviq''\n| Ship namesake=[[Inupiaq language|Inupiaq]] for \"[[walrus]]\"\n| Ship owner=[[Edison Chouest Offshore]]\n| Ship operator=\n| Ship registry=[[Galliano, Louisiana|Galliano]], [[Louisiana]], {{USA}}<ref name=\"abs\" />\n| Ship route=\n| Ship ordered=July 2009\n| Ship builder=*[[North American Shipbuilding]], [[Larose, Louisiana]]\n*[[LaShip]], [[Houma, Louisiana]]\n| Ship original cost=$200 million\n| Ship yard number=247\n| Ship way number=\n| Ship laid down=3 February 2010\n| Ship launched=1 November 2011\n| Ship christened=24 March 2012\n| Ship completed=20 April 2012\n| Ship acquired=\n| Ship maiden voyage=\n| Ship in service=2012\u2013\n| Ship out of service=\n| Ship identification=*{{IMO number|9579016}}\n*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: WDG2524\n*{{MMSI|367141000}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9579016|shipname=Aiviq|accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref>\n| Ship fate=\n| Ship status=In service<ref name=\"equasis\" />\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship class=\n| Ship type=[[Anchor handling tug supply vessel]] (AHTS)\n| Ship tonnage=*{{GT|12,892}}\n*{{NetT|3,867}}\n*{{DWT|4,129}}\n| Ship displacement=\n| Ship length={{convert|110|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam={{convert|24.4|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height=\n| Ship draught={{convert|8.6|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth={{convert|10.4|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship ice class=[[American Bureau of Shipping|ABS]] A3\n| Ship power=4{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar]] C280-12 (4{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}4,060{{nbsp}}kW)\n| Ship propulsion=*Two [[Ducted propeller|ducted]] [[controllable-pitch propeller]]s\n*Three [[bow thruster]]s and two stern thrusters\n| Ship speed=*{{convert|15|kn}} in open water\n*{{convert|5|kn}} in {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on}} ice\n| Ship capacity=\n| Ship crew=28; accommodation for 64\n| Ship aircraft facilities = Helideck\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Aiviq''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[icebreaker|icebreaking]] [[anchor handling tug supply vessel]] (AHTS) owned by [[Edison Chouest Offshore]] (ECO). The $200 million vessel was built in 2012 by [[North American Shipbuilding]] in [[Larose, Louisiana]] and LaShip in [[Houma, Louisiana]]. She has been chartered by [[Royal Dutch Shell]] to support oil exploration and drilling in the [[Chukchi Sea]] off [[Alaska]].<ref name=\"workboat\" /> The primary task of the vessel is towing and laying anchors for drilling rigs, but she is also equipped for [[Oil spill#Cleanup and recovery|oil spill response]].<ref name=AnchorageDailyNews2011-12-06>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.adn.com/2011/12/05/2204274/shell-about-to-unveil-200-million.html \n |title=Shell to unveil icebreaker for Arctic Alaska offshore drilling: Vessel will work waters off Alaska during oil exploration \n |publisher=[[Anchorage Daily News]] \n |date=2011-12-06 \n |accessdate=2012-01-26 \n |author=Lisa Demer \n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107133034/http://www.adn.com/2011/12/05/2204274/shell-about-to-unveil-200-million.html\n |archivedate=2012-01-07\n}} ()\n</ref><ref name=MarineLink2012-01-17>{{cite news|url=http://www.marinelink.com/news/exploration-icebreaker342119.aspx |title=Shell Awaits New Giant Icebreaker |publisher=[[Marinelink]] |date=2012-01-17 |accessdate=2012-01-26 |author=Susan Buchanan |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127101801/http://www.marinelink.com/news/exploration-icebreaker342119.aspx |archivedate=2012-01-27 }} ()</ref>\n\nThe vessel has been called the world's most powerful privately owned icebreaker.<ref name=maritimeExecutive2018-01-02/>\n\n==Construction==\n\nIn July 2009, Edison Chouest Offshore won a $150 million contract for the construction of an icebreaking anchor handling tug supply (AHTS) vessel for [[Royal Dutch Shell]]. The {{convert|360|ft|m|adj=on}} vessel, largest ever built by the company, would be used to support Shell's drilling operations in the [[Beaufort Sea]] and [[Chukchi Sea]] off [[Alaska]].<ref>[http://www.dailycomet.com/article/20090722/HURBLOG/907229884/1223?Title=Chouest-scores-new-icebreaker-contract Chouest scores new icebreaker contract]. dailycomet.com, 22 July 2009. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> In January 2010, it was announced that the  vessel would be constructed in [[Louisiana]]. The hull and the superstructure would be built in the company's own shipyard [[North American Shipbuilding]] in [[Larose, Louisiana|Larose]] in two separate units while the final assembly of the vessel would take place at LaShip, also owned by Edison Chouest, in [[Houma, Louisiana|Houma]]. In all, the construction would take just over two years and provide work for about 800 people.<ref>[http://www.dailycomet.com/article/20100122/ARTICLES/100129748 Icebreaker to be built locally]. dailycomet.com, 22 January 2010. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n\n[[Keel laying|Laid down]] on 3 February 2010,<ref name=\"abs\" /> the newbuilding \"Hull 247\" was presented to Shell executives on 30 September 2011. By then, the price of the vessel had climbed to $200 million due to material and equipment factors, such as the price of steel.<ref>[http://www.wwltv.com/news/Shell-execs-get-glimpse-of-all-new-icebreaker-ship-design-130914038.html Shell execs get glimpse of 'all new' icebreaker ship design] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808041748/http://www.wwltv.com/news/Shell-execs-get-glimpse-of-all-new-icebreaker-ship-design-130914038.html |date=2014-08-08 }}. WWLTV, 1 October 2011. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref><ref>[http://www.chron.com/business/article/Shell-hopes-to-break-the-ice-on-Arctic-drilling-2197495.php Shell hopes to break the ice on Arctic drilling]. Chron, 30 September 2011. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> The vessel was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 1 November 2011.<ref name=\"abs\" /> According to Edison Chouest spokesman Gary Chouest, ''\"It [''Aiviq''] will be the world's largest and most powerful anchor-handling icebreaker.\"''<ref name=AnchorageDailyNews2011-12-06/>\n\nIn 2011, Shell invited [[Inupiak]] schoolchildren to submit essays suggesting names for the vessel. Twelve-year-old Elizabeth Itta submitted the winning essay, describing how the [[Walrus]], \"Aiviq\" in the Inupiak language, use their tusks to break ice. She won a cash prize for her school and an invitation to attend the ship's launching ceremony on 24 March 2012.<ref name=Shell>{{cite news|url=http://www.shell.us/home/content/usa/aboutshell/projects_locations/alaska/events_news/12092012_walrus.html |title=Winner of Ice Breaker Naming Contest |publisher=[[Shell Oil]] |date=2011-12-09 |accessdate=2012-01-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514135634/http://www.shell.us/home/content/usa/aboutshell/projects_locations/alaska/events_news/12092012_walrus.html |archivedate=2012-05-14 }} ()</ref><ref>[http://shipbuildingtribune.com/2012/03/26/usa-edison-chouest-offshore-shipyard-christens-shells-new-icebreaker-aiviq/ USA: Edison Chouest Offshore Shipyard Christens Shell\u2019s New Icebreaker Aiviq] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712122557/http://shipbuildingtribune.com/2012/03/26/usa-edison-chouest-offshore-shipyard-christens-shells-new-icebreaker-aiviq/ |date=2012-07-12 }}. ShipbuildingTribune.com, 26 March 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> The vessel went for sea trials in April and was delivered on 20 April 2012.<ref name=\"abs\" /><ref name=\"marinelog1april\">[http://www.marinelog.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2208 Giant ice-class AHTS on sea trials following completion by Chouest] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214072026/http://www.marinelog.com/index.php?option=com_content |date=2012-02-14 }}. MarineLog, 1 April 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe construction of the new icebreaker and Shell's Arctic drilling operation off Alaska raised concerns about the ability of the [[United States Coast Guard]] to operate in ice-infested waters since at the time the Coast Guard had only one operational icebreaker, {{USCGC|Healy}}.<ref>[http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-07-18/shell-led-arctic-push-finds-u-dot-s-dot-shy-in-icebreakers-energy Shell-Led Arctic Push Finds U.S. Shy in Icebreakers: Energy]. [[Bloomberg BusinessWeek]], 18 July 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, it was reported that Edison Chouest would build two [[Polar Class 3]] anchor-handling tug supply (AHTS) vessels at the company's LaShip shipyard in Houma, Louisiana. Unlike ''Aiviq'', the new vessels would have been fitted with [[Rolls-Royce Holdings|Rolls-Royce]] [[azimuth thruster]]s instead of conventional shaftlines and rudders.<ref>[http://www.rolls-royce.com/media/press-releases/yr-2015/pr-040315-rr-to-supply-propulsion-and-deck.aspx Rolls-Royce to supply propulsion and deck machinery to a new vessel for Edison Chouest]. Rolls-Royce, 4 March 2015. {{retrieved|accessdate=2016-05-14}}</ref> However, in November 2015 it was reported that Edison Chouest might have canceled the vessels following Shell's decision to halt Arctic oil exploration.<ref>[http://www.marinelog.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=10031:chouest-said-to-have-canceled-arctic-ahts-duo&Itemid=230 Chouest said to have canceled Arctic AHTS duo]. MarineLog, 9 November 2015. {{retrieved|\u0259ccessdate=2016-05-14}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n{{expand section|date=January 2013}}\n\n=== Grounding of ''Kulluk'' ===\n[[File:KullukAground 1jan2013.JPG|thumb|left|''Kulluk'' aground on the southeast side of Sitkalidak Island, Alaska, on 1 January 2013.]]\nOn 27 December 2012, while ''Aiviq'' was towing the mobile offshore drilling unit ''[[Kulluk]]'' off the coast of [[Kodiak Island]], [[Alaska]], the towing line between the icebreaker and the drilling rig parted due to a mechanical failure of the towing shackle.<ref name=\"sitrep\">[http://dec.alaska.gov/spar/perp/response/sum_fy13/121227201/121227201_sr_02.pdf M/V Aiviq Tow-Gulf of Alaska]. Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation, 28 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref> Shortly after the tow had been regained, the main engines of ''Aiviq'' failed and the vessel lost propulsion power in {{convert|20|ft|m|0|adj=on}} seas. In the following morning, power was successfully restored on one of the four main engines and the vessel was able to hold position in the heavy weather.<ref name=\"aiviq1\">[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1669855/MV-Aiviq-loses-power-at-sea MV Aiviq loses power at sea]. Aiviq Tow - Gulf of Alaska, Unified Command, 28 December 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-12-28}}</ref> [[United States Coast Guard]] cutter [[USCGC Alex Haley (WMEC-39)|USCGC ''Alex Haley'']] was dispatched to the scene to monitor the situation.<ref>[http://d17.uscgnews.com/go/doc/4007/1669275/ Coast Guard assists tug and tow in Gulf of Alaska] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102220503/http://d17.uscgnews.com/go/doc/4007/1669275/ |date=2013-01-02 }}. United States Coast Guard, 28 December 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> In response to the incident, the Coast Guard, Shell and Edison Chouest established a Unified Command to coordinate the operation.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1669883/Unified-Command-established Unified Command established]. Unified Command, 28 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> Shell-contracted vessels [[MV Guardsman|''Guardsman'']] and [[MV Nanuq|''Nanuq'']] were also en route to the scene.<ref name=\"aiviq1\" />\n\nOn 29 December, the Unified Command authorized the drilling rig to drop its anchor to slow its drift towards the coast and ordered the Coast Guard to evacuate the 18 crew members on ''Kulluk'' by helicopter as a precaution.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1669911/Unified-Command-Statement-3 Unified Command Statement #3]. Unified Command, 29 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref><ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1669915/Unified-Command-authorizes-Kulluk-to-drop-anchor-to-slow-drift Unified Command authorizes Kulluk to drop anchor to slow drift]. Unified Command, 29 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> [[Sikorsky HH-60 Jayhawk]] helicopters operated by the Coast Guard also delivered essential equipment parts to ''Aiviq'' and later power was restored on all four engines. Together with ''Nanuq'', ''Aiviq'' was able to hold the drilling rig stationary during the crew evacuation and later continue towing the vessel away from the coast.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1669919/Incident-response-continues-second-engine-running-on-Aiviq- Incident response continues, second engine running on Aiviq]. Unified Command, 29 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref><ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670119/Update-6-18-personnel-on-Kulluk-safely-evacuated-Aiviq-s-4-engines-functioning Update #6: 18 personnel on Kulluk safely evacuated, Aiviq\u2019s 4 engines functioning]. Unified Command, 29 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 December, the tow lines of ''Aiviq'' and ''Nanuq'' parted again, and ''Kulluk'' began drifting towards the coast. Another tugboat, the 10,000-horsepower [[MV Alert|''Alert'']] operated by [[Crowley Maritime|Crowley Marine Services]],<ref>[http://www.tugboatinformation.com/tug.cfm?id=1176 Alert]. Tugboat-information.com. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> also arrived to the scene from [[Prince William Sound]].<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670283/Update-9-Kulluk-tow-lines-separated-Alert-on-scene Update #9: Kulluk tow lines separated; Alert on scene]. Unified Command, 30 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> Shortly after midnight, ''Alert'' was able to secure connection to the {{convert|400|ft|m|adj=on}} towing line previously used by ''Aiviq'' and later in the morning the icebreaker had also reconnected to ''Kulluk'' about {{convert|19|nmi}} southeast from Kodiak Island.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670343/Update-10-Kulluk-under-tow-by-Aiviq-and-Alert Update #10: Kulluk under tow by Aiviq and Alert]. Unified Command, 31 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> USCGC ''Alex Haley'' also returned to the scene from Kodiak, where the cutter had repaired her fouled port propeller, and relieved the crew of [[USCGC Spar (WLB-206)|USCGC ''Spar'']] as on scene commander. The helicopter crews were also preparing to deploy several technicians aboard the drilling rig to evaluate the condition of the towing lines.<ref name=\"uscg1\">[http://www.uscgnews.com/go/doc/4007/1670651/ Coast Guard crews continue battling fierce storm to assist Kulluk near Kodiak, Alaska] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105174055/http://www.uscgnews.com/go/doc/4007/1670651/ |date=2013-01-05 }}. United States Coast Guard, 31 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n\nLater in the evening, ''Kulluk'' was again set adrift after the Coast Guard ordered ''Alert'' to separate from the rig, now only {{convert|4|nmi}} from the nearest point of land, to maintain the safety of the nine crew members on board the tug in nearly {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=on}} seas.<ref name=\"uscg1\" /><ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670671/Update-11-Kulluk-is-adrift-four-miles-from-nearest-point-of-land Kulluk is adrift; four miles from nearest point of land]. Unified Command, 31 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> Only moments later, ''Kulluk'' was grounded near the uninhabited [[Sitkalidak Island]] at a depth of about {{convert|32|-|48|ft|m}}.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670687/Unified-Command-Update-12-Kulluk-grounded-vessel-condition-not-yet-confirmed Unified Command Update #12: Kulluk grounded, vessel condition not yet confirmed]. Unified Command, 31 December 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n\nThe salvage operation was awarded to the Dutch [[marine salvage|salvage company]] [[Smit International]].<ref name=\"salvage\">[http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1671847/CORRECTION-Update-18-Salvage-Assessment-Team-Safely-Boards-Drilling-Unit Update #18: Salvage Assessment Team Safely Boards Drilling Unit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106030624/http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1671847/CORRECTION-Update-18-Salvage-Assessment-Team-Safely-Boards-Drilling-Unit |date=2013-01-06 }}. Unified Command, 2 January 2013. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-04}}</ref> A team of five salvage experts boarded ''Kulluk'' on 2 January 2013 to assess the structural integrity of the grounded drilling barge.<ref name=\"salvage\" /> On 3 January, it was reported that ''Kulluk'' had suffered damage since the grounding but its structural integrity had not been compromised and there have been no leaks from the rig's fuel tanks.<ref>[http://www.ktuu.com/news/kulluk-has-suffered-damage-since-grounding-hasnt-leaked-oil-010312,0,5074823.story Kulluk Has Suffered Damage Since Grounding, Hasn't Leaked Oil] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107211903/http://www.ktuu.com/news/kulluk-has-suffered-damage-since-grounding-hasnt-leaked-oil-010312,0,5074823.story |date=2013-01-07 }}. KTUU.com, 3 January 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-04}}</ref> At the time of the grounding, ''Kulluk'' was carrying 139,000 gallons of diesel fuel and 12,000 gallons of lubricating and hydraulic oil.<ref>[https://www.piersystem.com/go/doc/5507/1670699/Unified-Command-Update-13 Unified Command Update #13]. Unified Command, 1 January 2013. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> By 4 January, 14 vessels had been mobilized for the recovery operation and the [[United States Department of Defense]] provided two [[Boeing CH-47 Chinook]] helicopters to transport heavy salvage gear to the site.<ref>[http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1674171/ Update #21: Extensive Air and Sea Activity as Kulluk Recovery Operations Continue] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20130216085225/http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1674171/ |date=2013-02-16 }}. Unified Command, 4 January 2013. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref>\n\n''Kulluk'' was successfully refloated on 6 January and towed to a sheltered location in [[Kiliuda Bay]], some {{convert|30|nmi}} from the original grounding location, on the following day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Grounded Shell oil-drilling ship refloated|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/grounded-shell-oil-drilling-ship-refloated|publisher=The Associated Press|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1675595/#.UOs5H3h9SHd Update #34: Kulluk arrives safely at Kiliuda Bay, will undergo assessment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111013208/http://www.kullukresponse.com/go/doc/5507/1675595#.UOs5H3h9SHd |date=2013-01-11 }}. Unified Command, 7 January 2013. {{retrieved | accessdate=2013-01-07}}</ref> After the rig was brought to a shipyard in [[Singapore]] on board a heavy-lift vessel, Shell decided not to repair the damages and sold the drilling unit for recycling in China.<ref>[http://www.petroleumnews.com/pntruncate/81694360.shtml Shell responds to BOEM]. Petroleum News, 5 January 2014. {{retrieved|accessdate=2014-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn the investigation report published by the United States Coast Guard on 2 April 2014, the initiating event to the casualty was identified as the failure of a 120-ton apex [[shackle]] which was considered undersized for towing ''Kulluk'' in such environmental conditions. The 90-feet [[Catenary#Anchoring of marine objects|catenary]] surge chain used to damp shock loads in the towing line was also deemed insufficient. According to the Coast Guard, the \"numerous and compounding preconditions\" that led to the casualty also included various operational issues such as the towing plans that were not adequate for the winter towing operation crossing the Gulf of Alaska and the crew's lack of towing experience in the Gulf of Alaska waters particularly during the wintertime.<ref name=\"accidentreport\">[https://www.dco.uscg.mil/Portals/9/DCO%20Documents/5p/CG-5PC/INV/docs/documents/Kulluk.pdf Report of Investigation into the Circumstances Surrounding the Multiple Related Marine Casualties and Grounding of the MODU KULLUK on December 31, 2012]. United States Coast Guard, 2 April 2014. {{retrieved|accessdate=2018-10-31}}</ref>\n\nIn the same report, it was also concluded that the likely cause for ''Aiviq''{{'}}s loss of main engine power was sea water in the fuel oil. After the casualty, sea water contamination was found in settling tanks, day tanks, main engine primary filters and main engine injectors. The design of the vessel allowed considerable amount of sea water to enter the stern deck and subsequently to the fuel oil tanks through overflow vents in heavy weather. There were also problems with fuel management practices onboard ''Aiviq''.<ref name=\"accidentreport\" />\n\n''Kulluk'''s movement south for the winter was at least in part motivated by an effort to avoid State of Alaska property taxes on oil and gas extraction equipment.<ref name=\"dispatch-ben\">{{Cite news | work = [[Alaska Dispatch]] | title = Did Alaska tax liability influence Shell Oil's latest Arctic fiasco? | url = http://www.alaskadispatch.com/article/did-alaska-tax-liability-influence-shell-oils-latest-arctic-fiasco | first = Ben | last = Anderson | date = {{date|2013-01-03|mdy}} | accessdate = {{date|2011-11-15|mdy}}}}</ref>\n\n===Proposed sale to US Coast Guard===\nOn 14 May 2015, [[US Congressman]] [[Duncan D. Hunter|Duncan Hunter]] of California, began advocating for the acquisition of ''Aiviq'' by the [[US Coast Guard]] (USCG) due to an availability gap caused by USCG's retirement of the icebreaker [[USCGC Healy (WAGB-20)|USCGC ''Healy'']].<ref name=\"SDUT Hunter\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=[Coast Guard Adm. Charles] Michel said the Coast Guard\u2019s commandant had personally visited the vessel and found it \"not suitable for military service without substantial refit.\" He said the Coast Guard does not operate non-military icebreakers.}}</ref> USCG repeatedly turned down Hunter's continued proposals, citing the vessel's unsuitability for military operations and being less-capable than ''Healy'', with Coast Guard Admiral [[Charles D. Michel|Charles Michel]] stating ''Aiviq'' is \"Not suitable for military service without substantial refit. [...] We have very specific requirements for our vessels, including international law requirements for assertion of things like navigation rights. This vessel does not just break ice.\"<ref name=\"SDUT Hunter\" /><ref name=\"MAREX\">{{cite web|title=Rep. Young Pushes Coast Guard to Consider the Aiviq|url=https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/rep-young-pushes-coast-guard-to-consider-the-aiviq|publisher=The Maritime Executive|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122094801/https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/rep-young-pushes-coast-guard-to-consider-the-aiviq|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 July 2016|quote=Without modification, the Aiviq is somewhat less capable than the Coast Guard medium icebreaker Healy, and is not in the same class as the heavy icebreaker due to retire next decade, the Polar Star.}}</ref>\n\nControversy arose after it was published that Congressman Hunter had received campaign funding from ''Aiviq''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s owner, [[Edison Chouest Offshore]], and contributors connected to the owner, six days before initially advocating the vessel's sale to USCG.<ref name=\"SDUT Hunter 2\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=The Chouest funds were all received May 8, 2015 \u2014 six days before the Coast Guard was to have an acquisitions hearing before a Congressional subcommittee chaired by Hunter.}}</ref> Edison Chouest's contributions to Hunter have made them the congressman's second largest donor.<ref name=\"SDUT Hunter 3\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=Contributors connected to the Aiviq\u2019s owner, Louisiana-based shipbuilder Edison Chouest Offshore, have given at least $18,000 to Hunter\u2019s campaign since January 2015. That\u2019s a fraction of the $911,000 that Hunter raised during that time period. It makes Chouest the second most generous supporter of Hunter, according to review by The San Diego Union-Tribune of campaign finance records.}}</ref> The company's donations came as Congressman Hunter was under investigation for misuse of campaign funds.<ref name=\"SDUT Hunter 4\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=The money entered Hunter\u2019s campaign coffers at the height of a problem he has since acknowledged with thousands of dollars of campaign funds that were spent on personal expenses \u2014 such as $1,137 for oral surgery the following month.}}</ref> On 12 July 2016, Hunter's advocacy for the vessel's acquisition was joined by US Congressman [[Don Young]] of Alaska.<ref name=\"SDUT Young\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=At the subcommittee hearing July 12, Hunter had an ally in Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, who also believes the Coast Guard does not require military-grade vessels for ice breaking. He described Michel\u2019s justification for not wanting to lease the Aiviq because it\u2019s not a military vessel as \u201ca bulls--- answer.\u201d Since 2015, Edison Chouest Offshore was Young\u2019s top campaign contributor, donating at least $28,300, according to Opensecrets.org.}}</ref> ''Aiviq''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s owner was Congressman Young's largest campaign donor at that time.<ref name=\"Young contribs\">{{cite web|title=Rep. Don Young - Alaska District 01 - Contributors 2015 - 2016|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/members-of-congress/contributors?cid=N00007999&cycle=2016|website=[[OpenSecrets]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122100139/https://www.opensecrets.org/members-of-congress/contributors?cid=N00007999&cycle=2016|archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nCongressman Hunter's office estimated it would cost US$33 million a year to lease, or US$150 million to buy ''Aiviq'' outright.<ref name=\"Def News\">{{cite web|author1=Joe Gould|title=US Lawmaker Wants Pre-Owned Ice Ship Over Coast Guard Objections|url=https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2016/09/30/us-lawmaker-wants-pre-owned-ice-ship-over-coast-guard-objections/|website=[[Defense News]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180122102528/https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2016/09/30/us-lawmaker-wants-pre-owned-ice-ship-over-coast-guard-objections/|archivedate=2018-01-22|date=30 September 2016|quote=Hunter claims the cost to charter an existing vessel, called the Aiviq, would be $33 million per year to lease and $150 million to buy.|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"SDUT Hunter 5\">{{cite web|author1=Morgan Cook|title=Hunter pushes Coast Guard to lease or buy ship owned by top campaign donor|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122090806/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/watchdog/sd-me-watchdog-icebreaker-20161013-story.html|archivedate=22 January 2018|date=13 October 2016|quote=Last month, Hunter asked Republican House leadership for money to be included in \u201cany suitable and forthcoming appropriations vehicle\u201d for lease or purchase of a medium icebreaker, according to a Sept. 20 letter Hunter\u2019s office released to the Union-Tribune on Thursday. The letter estimated the costs to charter the Aiviq at $33 million per year to lease, or $150 million to buy.}}</ref>\n\n=== Proposed sale to Canada ===\n\nSince 2016, [[Davie Shipbuilding]] has offered ''Aiviq'' together with other out-of-work offshore icebreakers to the [[Canadian Coast Guard]] as a replacement for {{ship|CCGS|Louis S. St-Laurent}}.<ref>[http://www.davie.ca/pdf/Aiviq.pdf Aiviq - Polar Icebreaker]. Davie Shipbuilding. {{retrieved|accessdate=2016-06-13}}</ref> However, recent reports indicate that the Canadian Coast Guard is not interested in the vessel.<ref>[http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1091392/brise-glaces-davie Brise-glaces et Davie : des doutes sur la volont\u00e9 d\u2019Ottawa]. Radio-Canada, 26 March 2018. {{retrieved|accessdate=2018-03-28}}</ref> In June 2018, it was announced that the Canadian government ended up partnering with Davie Shipbuilding, but using three ships from [[Viking Supply Ships]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.marinelog.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=29600:canada-taps-davie-for-three-ahts-conversion-medium-icebreakers&Itemid=231 | title = Canada taps Davie for three AHTS-conversion medium icebreakers | date = 2018-06-22 | work = Marine Log | publisher = Simmons-Boardman Publishing}}</ref>\n\n==General characteristics==\n''Aiviq'' is {{convert|110|m|ftin}} [[length overall|long overall]] and {{convert|95.5|m|ftin}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]]. Her hull has a beam of {{convert|24.4|m|ft}} and depth of {{convert|10.4|m|ftin}}.<ref name=\"abs\">{{csr|register=ABS|id=12185769|shipname=Aiviq|accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref> Fully laden, she draws {{convert|8.6|m|ftin}} of water.<ref name=\"shell\">[http://www.shell.us/home/content/usa/aboutshell/projects_locations/alaska/events_news/03262012_ice-vessel.html Shell Takes Delivery of New Ice Class Vessel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514141647/http://www.shell.us/home/content/usa/aboutshell/projects_locations/alaska/events_news/03262012_ice-vessel.html |date=2012-05-14 }}. Shell, 24 March 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-04-14}}</ref> Since ''Aiviq'' is an anchor handling tug and supply vessel, she is fitted with a large towing winch located amidships as well as chain lockers and storage tanks for both liquid and dry bulk cargo under the main deck.<ref name=\"ga\">[http://www.boem.gov/uploadedFiles/BOEM/Oil_and_Gas_Energy_Program/Plans/Regional_Plans/Alaska_Exploration_Plans/2012_Shell_Beaufort_EP/Appendix%20K%20-%20Ice%20Management.pdf Appendix K: Ice management plan]. Shell Offshore Inc. Pages 41\u201343. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref> Her [[gross tonnage]] is 12,892, [[net tonnage]] 3,867 and [[deadweight tonnage]] 4,129 tonnes.<ref name=\"abs\" />\n\n''Aiviq'' is powered by four [[V12 engine|12-cylinder]] [[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar]] C280-12 [[Four-stroke engine|four stroke]] medium speed [[diesel engine]]s, each producing {{convert|4060|kW|hp|abbr=on}} at 1,000 rpm. The engines are coupled to two {{convert|4.6|m|ft|adj=on}} [[Schottel (company)|Schottel]] [[controllable-pitch propeller]] in [[Ducted propeller|nozzles]] via [[Flender]] reduction gearboxes.<ref name=\"abs\" /><ref name=\"pride\">[http://www.professionalmariner.com/American-Ship-Review-2013/Aiviq-Pride-of-Shells-Alaskan-drilling-fleet/ Aiviq: Pride of Shell\u2019s Alaskan drilling fleet]. Professional Mariner, 16 October 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> The propulsion system gives ''Aiviq'' a service speed of {{convert|15|kn}} in open water and {{convert|5|kn}} in {{convert|1|m|ftin|adj=on}} level ice, and a bollard pull of 200 metric tons.<ref name=\"shell\" /> She also has two 2,000&nbsp;kW shaft generators and four 1,700&nbsp;kW Caterpillar 3512C auxiliary diesel generators that provide power for onboard consumers, including the firefighting system. She has three [[bow thruster]]s, one of them of [[azimuth thruster|azimuthing]] fold-down type, and two stern thrusters that give her [[dynamic positioning]] capability. For redundancy and improved handling, she has two high-lift rudders.<ref name=\"abs\" /><ref name=\"workboat\">[http://www.workboat.com/newsdetail.aspx?id=13632 Breaking the Ice] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231203222/http://www.workboat.com/newsdetail.aspx?id=13632 |date=2014-12-31 }}. WorkBoat.com, 15 May 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref><ref name=\"ga\" /> The propellers of ''Aiviq'' are reportedly designed to be quieter than normal in order to be less disruptive to local marine life.<ref name=Ktuu2011-11-14>{{cite news|url=http://articles.ktuu.com/2011-11-14/arctic-offshore-drilling_30399477 |title=Shell Offshore: Arctic Icebreaker Takes Shape |publisher=[[KTUU]] |date=2011-11-14 |accessdate=2012-01-27 |author=Ted Land |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119010412/http://articles.ktuu.com/2011-11-14/arctic-offshore-drilling_30399477 |archivedate=2012-01-19 }}</ref>\n\n''Aiviq'' is classified by the [[American Bureau of Shipping]]. Her ice class, ABS A3, indicates that she is strengthened for navigation in polar ice conditions with the presence of multiyear ice floes. Furthermore, the notation \"Ice Breaker\" states that she is designed and constructed for breaking ice to open navigable channels for other ships.<ref name=\"abs\" /><ref name=\"MAREX\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=maritimeExecutive2018-01-02>\n{{cite news \n| url         = https://www.maritime-executive.com/editorials/an-out-of-the-blue-icebreaker-opportunity\n| title       = An Out-of-the-Blue Icebreaker Opportunity\n| work        = [[Maritime Executive]]\n| author      = [[Pierre LeBlanc]]\n| date        = 2018-01-02\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20180107085857/https://www.maritime-executive.com/editorials/an-out-of-the-blue-icebreaker-opportunity\n| archivedate = 2018-01-07\n| accessdate  = 2018-11-28\n| url-status     = live \n| quote       = The m/v Aiviq is a Polar Class 3 icebreaker built by North American Shipbuilders in 2012. It is reported to be the world\u2019s most powerful icebreaker privately owned.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Category:2011 ships]]\n[[Category:Icebreakers of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Tupsumato", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aiviq"}
{"title_page": "Julian Edelman", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American football wide receiver and punt returner}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name         = Julian Edelman\n| image        = Julian Edelman 2014.JPG\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = Edelman with the Patriots in 2013\n| current_team = New England Patriots\n| number       = 11\n| position     = [[Wide receiver]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1986|5|22}}\n| birth_place  = [[Redwood City, California]]\n| height_ft    = 5\n| height_in    = 10 \n| weight_lbs   = 198\n| high_school  = [[Woodside High School (California)|Woodside]]<br>([[Woodside, California]]) \n| college      = [[Kent State Golden Flashes football|Kent State]]\n| draftyear    = 2009\n| draftround   = 7\n| draftpick    = 232\n| pastteams    =\n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|2009}}\u2013present)\n| status       = Active \n| highlights   =\n* 3\u00d7 [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLIX|XLIX]], [[Super Bowl LI|LI]], [[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]])\n* [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award|Super Bowl MVP]] ([[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]])\n| statseason   = 2019\n| statweek     = \n| statlabel1   = Receptions\n| statvalue1   = 599\n| statlabel2   = Receiving yards\n| statvalue2   = 6,507\n| statlabel3   = Receiving touchdowns\n| statvalue3   = 36\n| statlabel4   = Rushing yards\n| statvalue4   = 391\n|statlabel5= Passing yards\n| statvalue5= 90\n|statlabel6= Passing touchdowns\n|statvalue6= 1\n| statlabel7   = Total return yards\n| statvalue7   = 2,612\n| statlabel8   = Return touchdowns\n| statvalue8   = 4\n| nflnew       = julianedelman/238498\n| pfr          = EdelJu00\n}}\n\n'''Julian Francis Edelman''' (born May 22, 1986) is an [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] and [[punt returner]] for the [[New England Patriots]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Kent State Golden Flashes football|Kent State]] and the [[College of San Mateo]] as a [[quarterback]]. He was drafted by the Patriots in the seventh round of the [[2009 NFL Draft]]. Edelman primarily plays on offense and as a punt returner; he has also been pressed into service as a [[cornerback]] at times when the Patriots have been shorthanded on defense.\n\nEdelman is one of the most productive receivers in post-season history, ranking second overall (behind [[Jerry Rice]]) in both post-season receiving yards and post-season receptions.  He has played in four Super Bowls ([[Super Bowl XLVI|XLVI]], [[Super Bowl XLIX|XLIX]], [[Super Bowl LI|LI]] and [[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]]). In each of the last three, he led all wide receivers in receiving yards. He was named [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award|Super Bowl MVP]] for Super Bowl LIII, in which he had 10 catches for 141 yards receiving, more than half of his team's total receiving yardage. He holds the Super Bowl records for career punt returns (8) and first-half receptions in a single game (7).\n\n==Early years==\nEdelman was born in [[Redwood City, California]], to Angela (n\u00e9e Gole) and Frank Edelman, a mechanic who owns an A-1 Auto Tech.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/12659571 |title=Julian Edelman enjoys his moment |date=February 19, 2015 |website=ESPN.com}}</ref> He has two siblings, Jason and Nicole.<ref>[http://www.patriots.com/team/roster/Julian-Edelman/1f41cf38-740b-4d2a-9109-7e13b48567e7 Julian Edelman profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131230846/http://www.patriots.com/team/roster/Julian-Edelman/1f41cf38-740b-4d2a-9109-7e13b48567e7 |date=January 31, 2012 }}, Patriots.com; accessed November 6, 2015.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://search.ancestry.com/search/db.aspx?dbid=5247 |title=California Birth Index, 1905\u20131995 |publisher=Ancestry |access-date=February 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2014/01/16/julian-edelman-took-back-road-nfl/Qbv5QnIQh9BpRn9ZetrSRO/story.html |title=Julian Edelman took the 'back road' to the NFL |website=BostonGlobe.com |access-date=April 9, 2015}}</ref> Originally raised as a [[Christians|Christian]], his ancestry includes [[Greeks|Greek]], [[English people|English]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], Irish, [[Ashkenazi Jewish]], and [[Germans|German]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://njjewishnews.com/kaplanskorner/2009/09/21/edelman-mot/ |title=Edelman MOT? \u00bb Kaplan's Korner on Jews and Sports |date=September 21, 2009 |website=Njjewishnews.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108212449/http://njjewishnews.com/kaplanskorner/2009/09/21/edelman-mot/ |archive-date=November 8, 2014 |access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> His mother was born in [[Kitchener, Ontario]], Canada, to German parents who had lived in [[Belgium]].<ref name=\"relnt1\">Stated in ''Relentless: A Memoir'', Julian Edelman, 2017, Hachette Books</ref>\n\nHe was the quarterback for [[Woodside High School (California)|Woodside High School]] in [[Woodside, California]], and as a senior, he led the Wildcats to a 13\u20130 record in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/high-schools/woodside-wildcats-(woodside,ca)/football-fall-04/schedule.htm |title=Schedule \u2013 Woodside Wildcats 2004 Football (CA) |website=www.maxpreps.com |access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref> During his high school career, Edelman had 2,237 yards and 29 touchdowns passing, in addition to 964 yards and 13 [[touchdown]]s rushing.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Yang |first=Nicole |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/new-england-patriots/2017/10/24/5-things-we-learned-from-julian-edelmans-new-memoir-relentless |title=5 things we learned from Julian Edelman's new memoir 'Relentless' |date=October 24, 2017 |work=Boston.com |access-date=December 25, 2017 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nAfter high school, Edelman spent a year attending the [[College of San Mateo]]. There, he threw for 1,312 yards and 14 touchdowns, rushed for a school-record 1,253 yards and 17 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.collegeofsanmateo.edu/football/alumni/alumni_nfl.php |title=NFL Bulldogs |website=College of San Mateo Bulldog Athletics |publisher=College of San Mateo |access-date=April 21, 2016}}</ref> He then transferred to [[Kent State University]], where he majored in [[business management]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kent.edu/magazine/news/11-fast-facts-about-julian-edelman |title=11 Fast Facts About Julian Edelman |website=www.kent.edu |access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref> At Kent State, Edelman was a three-year starter at quarterback. His senior year, Edelman was the Golden Flashes' leading passer, completing 56% of his passes (153 of 275 passes for 1,820 yards), throwing 13 touchdowns and 11 [[interceptions]]. He was also their leading rusher, gaining 1,370 yards on 215 attempts (an average of 6.4 yards per carry) and scoring 13 touchdowns. His total offense broke [[Joshua Cribbs]]'s single-season school record, set in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/players/1123460 |title=NFL Draft - CBSSports.com - NFLDraftScout.com |website=CBSSports.com}}</ref><ref name=\"whitmer\">{{Cite news |last=Whitmer |first=Michael |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2013/09/11/julian-edelman-evolving-into-patriots-versatile-standout/i2V7qCn0MwSJwK6JNmGjcJ/story.html |title=Versatile Julian Edelman ready for his biggest role? |date=September 12, 2013 |work=Boston Globe (online) |access-date=September 12, 2013 |publisher=The New York Times Company |location=Boston MA}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! colspan=\"9\"|Passing !! colspan=\"4\"|Rushing !! colspan=\"2\"|Combined\n|-\n! GP !! Cmp !! Att !! % !! Yds !! Y/A !! TD !! Int !! Rate !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD !! Total<br/>Yards !! Total<br/>TDs\n|-\n! [[2006 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2006]] !! [[2006 Kent State Golden Flashes football team|Kent State]]\n| 11 || 134 || 242 || 55.4 || 1,859 || 7.7 || 10 || 11 || 124.4 || 169 || 658 || 3.9 || 7 || 2,517 || 17 \n|-\n! [[2007 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2007]] !! [[2007 Kent State Golden Flashes football team|Kent State]]\n| 8 || 98 || 189 || 51.9 || 1,318 || 7.0 || 7 || 9 || 113.1 || 118 || 455 || 3.9 || 2 || 1,773 || 9 \n|-\n! [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]] !! [[2008 Kent State Golden Flashes football team|Kent State]]\n| 12 || 153 || 275 || 55.6 || 1,820 || 6.6 || 13 || 11 || 118.8 || 215 || 1,370 || 6.4 || 13 || 3,190 || 26 \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total || 31 || 385 || 706 || 54.5 || 4,997 || 7.1 || 30 || 31 || 119.2 || 502 || 2,483 || 4.9 || 22 || 7,480 || 52 \n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 5\n|    height in = 10\u215c\n|       weight = 195\n|         dash = 4.52\n|    ten split = 1.52\n| twenty split = 2.58\n|      shuttle = 3.92\n|   cone drill = 6.62\n|     vertical = 36 {{fraction|1|2}}\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 3\n|        bench = 14\n|         note = All values from Kent State [[Pro Day]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.draftscout.com/dsprofile.php?PlayerId=67858&DraftYear=2009 |title=Julian Edelman |publisher=draftscout.com |access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\nEdelman was not invited to the 2009 [[NFL Combine]]. At his March 12 Pro Day, he ran the [[20-yard shuttle|short shuttle]] in 3.92 seconds; the fastest time at the Combine that year was 3.96 seconds.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/2011/profiles/julian-edelman?id=238498 |title=National Football League: NFL Draft 2009 \u2013 Julian Edelman |website=nfl.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217203940/http://www.nfl.com/draft/2011/profiles/julian-edelman?id=238498 |archive-date=February 17, 2015 |access-date=April 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/top-performers#year=2009&workout=TWENTY_YARD_SHUTTLE&position=QB-RB-WR-TE-S-DL-LB-CB-OL-SPEC |title=NFL Events: Combine Top Performers |website=nfl.com |access-date=April 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New England Patriots]], who had conducted private workouts with Edelman before the [[2009 NFL Draft]], selected him with the 27th pick of the seventh round (232nd overall), ahead of [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]] quarterback [[Brian Hoyer]], who joined the Patriots as a [[free agent]]. Several analysts suggested that the Patriots may have selected Edelman for his potential in a [[Wildcat formation]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/stories/042709dnspogosselin.323e458.html |title=Non-combine players make their mark in draft |last=Gosselin |first=Rick |date=April 27, 2009 |website=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |access-date=July 27, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.enterprisenews.com/sports/x921226440/It-s-QB-or-not-QB-at-Pats-camp |title=It's QB or not QB at Pats camp |last=Farley |first=Glen |date=May 2, 2009 |website=[[The Enterprise (Brockton)]] |access-date=July 27, 2009}}</ref> On July 16, 2009, Edelman signed a four-year contract with the Patriots that included a $48,700 [[signing bonus]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Gasper |first=Christopher |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2009/07/18/brace_signs_with_patriots/ |title=Patriots beef up with Brace |date=July 18, 2009 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |access-date=July 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===2009 season: Rookie year===\n[[File:Julian Edelman.JPG|upright|thumb|Edelman in 2011]]\nEdelman, on August 13, 2009, in a pre-season game against the [[2009 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], returned a [[punt (gridiron football)|punt]] 75 yards, and made the team over former Eagles wide receiver [[Greg Lewis (wide receiver)|Greg Lewis]], for whom the Patriots had given up a fifth-round draft pick in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Reiss |first=Mike |url=http://archive.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/extra_points/2009/08/edelman_punt_re.html |title=Julian Edelman punt return rewind |work=Boston.com |access-date=December 29, 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nEdelman missed the Patriots' Week 1 game against the [[2009 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] with an ankle injury, but was activated for and made his first career start in the Patriots' 16\u20139 loss in Week 2 against the [[2009 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], which was also the first game [[Wes Welker]] had missed since becoming a Patriot in 2007. Edelman led all receivers with eight receptions for 98 yards, and added 38 yards on two [[kickoff return]]s and 2 yards on a punt return, for a total of 138 all-purpose yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200909200nyj.htm |title=New England Patriots at New York Jets \u2013 September 20th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nEdelman broke his arm in the Patriots' 59\u20130 rout of the [[2009 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], and did not accompany the Patriots on their trip to London to play the [[2009 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]. At the time of his injury, Edelman was leading all rookies with 21 receptions. He returned with the Patriots' Week 10 game against the [[2009 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], where he scored his first official NFL touchdown on a 9-yard reception from Brady.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911150clt.htm |title=New England Patriots at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 November 15th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen Welker was sidelined for the season after tearing his [[Anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] and [[Medial collateral ligament|MCL]] against the [[2009 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], Edelman was once again called on to fill Welker's role; Edelman caught 10 of the 15 passes thrown to him for 103 yards, the first 100-yard game of his NFL career. He finished the regular season with 37 receptions for 359 yards and one touchdown. He also made six punt returns as well as 11 kickoff returns combining 304 yards in all on 17 returns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201001030htx.htm |title=New England Patriots at Houston Texans \u2013 January 3rd, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the Patriots' [[2009\u201310 NFL playoffs#AFC: Baltimore Ravens 33, New England Patriots 14|Wild Card Round]] [[2009\u201310 NFL playoffs|playoff]] loss to the [[2009 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Edelman caught six passes from Brady for 44 yards, including both of the Patriots' touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201001100nwe.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots \u2013 January 10th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> Edelman became the first rookie to score two receiving touchdowns in one postseason game since [[David Sloan (American football)|David Sloan]] did so for the [[Detroit Lions]] in the [[1995 Detroit Lions season|1995]] season.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Amyx |first=Scott |url=https://medium.com/@ScottAmyx/story-of-strive-julian-edelman-and-the-art-of-bouncing-back-64e351cf6d2b |title=Story of Strive: Julian Edelman and the Art of Bouncing Back |date=September 22, 2017 |access-date=December 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2010 season===\nIn the 2010 season, Edelman saw a decrease in playing time; through 15 games, having just four receptions for 14 yards. In the Week 17 game against the [[2010 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], with Welker, [[Deion Branch]], and [[Aaron Hernandez]] inactive, Edelman capitalized with three receptions for a total of 72 yards, and also with a 94-yard punt return touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201101020nwe.htm |title=Miami Dolphins at New England Patriots \u2013 January 2nd, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> It was the first punt return touchdown by a Patriot since [[Troy Brown]] returned one against the [[2001 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] in the Week 17 of the [[2001 New England Patriots season|2001 season]], and the longest punt return in Patriots franchise history, eclipsing an 89-yard return by [[Mike Haynes (cornerback)|Mike Haynes]] in [[1976 New England Patriots season|1976]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.patriots.com/news/index.cfm?ac=pressreleasesdetail&pid=47072&pcid=47 |title=Game Notes: Patriots vs. Dolphins |date=January 2, 2011 |website=[[New England Patriots]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511213325/http://www.patriots.com/news/index.cfm?ac=pressreleasesdetail&pid=47072&pcid=47 |archive-date=May 11, 2011 |access-date=January 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEdelman set a franchise record by averaging 15.3 yards per return,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bostonherald.com/sports/football/patriots/view.bg?articleid=1356752 |title=Patriots & NFL: New England Patriots |website=bostonherald.com |access-date=April 9, 2015}}</ref> which was second in the league after the Bears' [[Devin Hester]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.patriotledger.com/sports/pros/x578417121/Secondary-education-continues-with-Patriots-for-versatile-Edelman |title=Secondary education continues with Patriots for versatile Edelman |last=Glen Farley |website=The Patriot Ledger, Quincy, MA |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017061734/http://www.patriotledger.com/sports/pros/x578417121/Secondary-education-continues-with-Patriots-for-versatile-Edelman |archive-date=October 17, 2013 |access-date=April 9, 2015}}</ref> For the 2010 season, Edelman played in 15 games with seven receptions for 86 yards and 321 return yards on 21 punt return opportunities.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/E/EdelJu00/gamelog/2010/ |title=Julian Edelman 2010 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref> In the [[2010\u201311 NFL playoffs#AFC: New York Jets 28, New England Patriots 21|Divisional Round]] against the [[2010 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], Edelman had a 12-yard reception in the 28\u201321 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201101160nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 New York Jets at New England Patriots \u2013 January 16th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2011 season: First Super Bowl appearance===\nDuring the 2011 season, Edelman was used primarily as a kick and punt returner. During the Patriots' Week 10 game against the [[2011 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], because of injuries to the Patriots' secondary, he was pressed into service as a [[defensive back]] during the fourth quarter; he earned his first tackle on defense by stopping running back [[LaDainian Tomlinson]] on a play in which Tomlinson injured his [[Medial collateral ligament|MCL]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nesn.com/2017/11/julian-edelman-recalls-injuring-ladainian-tomlinson-during-stint-as-cornerback/ |title=Julian Edelman Recalls Injuring LaDainian Tomlinson During Stint As Cornerback |last=Cox |first=Zack |date=November 15, 2017 |website=NESN.com |language=en |access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Patriots' Week 11 game on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' against the [[2011 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], he played defensive back in [[Nickelback (American football)|nickel and dime]] situations. He also returned a punt 72 yards for a touchdown, which helped him earn his first AFC Special Teams Player of the Week award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201111210nwe.htm |title=Kansas City Chiefs at New England Patriots \u2013 November 21st, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> In Week 12, he was nominated for the NFL's \"Hardest Working Man\" for his Week 12 performance against the [[2011 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], in which he made an open-field tackle on [[Vince Young]] to prevent a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d8248edf9/article/who-went-above-and-beyond-the-call-of-duty-in-week-12?module=HP11_cp |title=Who went above and beyond the call of duty in Week 12? |website=NFL.com |access-date=April 9, 2015}}</ref> For the 2011 season, Edelman played 13 games with four receptions for 34 yards and 584 return yards on 40 kickoff-punt combined returning opportunities.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/E/EdelJu00/gamelog/2011/ |title=Julian Edelman 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2012 AFC Championship game|AFC Championship]], on January 22, 2012, against the [[2011 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Edelman played on 27 of 67 offensive snaps at wide receiver, catching one pass that converted a third down attempt, and 27 of 73 defensive snaps at cornerback, often covering the Ravens' [[Anquan Boldin]]; Edelman was credited with a forced [[fumble]] on the Ravens' final drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201220nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots \u2013 January 22nd, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> The Patriots went on to win the AFC Championship, but lost [[Super Bowl XLVI]] to the [[2011 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]. Edelman had three kickoff returns for 73 net return yards in the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201202050nwe.htm |title=Super Bowl XLVI \u2013 New York Giants vs. New England Patriots \u2013 February 5th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2012 season===\nEdelman's snap count increased in the first two games of the 2012 season, including a Week 2 home loss to the [[2012 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]] in which he started over Wes Welker.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209160nwe.htm |title=Arizona Cardinals at New England Patriots \u2013 September 16th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> After suffering an injury in the Patriots' Week 3 loss to the [[2012 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Edelman was inactive for the next three games. He then saw limited duty until the Patriots' record-tying Week 11 win against the [[2012 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], in which he had a career day.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/2012/11/19/julian-edelman-enjoys-career-day-patriots-rout/wAoIkBACLpG9a7zsO08hvK/story.html |title=Julian Edelman enjoys career day in Patriots' rout \u2013 Boston.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121128170354/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/2012/11/19/julian-edelman-enjoys-career-day-patriots-rout/wAoIkBACLpG9a7zsO08hvK/story.html |archive-date=November 28, 2012}}</ref> Edelman caught five passes for 58 yards and a two-yard touchdown, picked up 47 yards on a single rushing attempt on a reverse play, and returned two punts for a total of 117 yards. The first of those punt returns was a 68-yard punt return for a touchdown, giving Edelman three punt return touchdowns, tying the Patriots franchise mark. In total, Edelman had 105 yards of total offense and 222 all-purpose yards with two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201211180nwe.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at New England Patriots \u2013 November 18th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFour days later, on [[Thanksgiving Day]], Edelman scored two more touchdowns in the second quarter of the Patriots' [[Butt fumble|victory]] over the [[2012 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], in which they tied a franchise record with five touchdowns and 35 points in one quarter; he recovered a Jets' fumble and returned it 22 yards on a kick-off return, and then caught a 56-yard touchdown pass from [[Tom Brady]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201211220nyj.htm |title=New England Patriots at New York Jets \u2013 November 22nd, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> Although he left early in the third quarter with a head injury, he nevertheless became the first player since the [[AFL\u2013NFL merger]] with both a receiving touchdown and a return touchdown in consecutive games. In a game against the [[2012 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] on December 2, Edelman broke his right foot and was placed on injured reserve. He missed the remainder of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/8665401/new-england-patriots-offense-numbers |title=New England Patriots' offense by the numbers |website=ESPN.com |access-date=April 9, 2015}}</ref> Overall in 2012, Edelman played in nine games with 21 receptions for 235 yards and 301 return yards on 20 kickoff-punt combined return opportunities.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/E/EdelJu00/gamelog/2012/ |title=Julian Edelman 2012 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2013 season===\nEdelman became a free agent after the 2012 season. He re-signed with New England on a one-year deal on April 10, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4741973/source-pats-edelman-reach-1-year-deal |title=Source: Pats, Edelman reach 1-year deal |website=ESPN.com |access-date=April 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2013 season opener, Edelman scored both of New England's touchdowns in their 23\u201321 win over the [[2013 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]]. He also had three punt returns for a total of 32 yards, which gave him a career total of 75 returns for 975 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309080buf.htm |title=New England Patriots at Buffalo Bills \u2013 September 8th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> Edelman became for the moment the NFL's all-time leader in career punt return average, with 13.0 yards per return, surpassing the 12.8-yard average of former Chicago Bear [[George McAfee]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2013/09/08/kyle-arrington-comes-big-twice-for-patriots-defense/st8QVsY9TCPDhnErNyn07L/story.html |title=Kyle Arrington comes up big twice for Patriots |website=BostonGlobe.com |access-date=April 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nEdelman had nine catches on 11 attempts for 110 yards and two touchdowns in a historic Week 12 Patriot home comeback victory over the [[2013 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]]; the Patriots overcame a 24-point halftime deficit to score 31 unanswered points and the winning field goal in the closing minutes of overtime. Edelman outperformed Denver's triplet star wide receivers combined.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201311240nwe.htm |title=Denver Broncos at New England Patriots \u2013 November 24th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> In Week 17, Edelman became the third Patriots player in team history to catch over 100 passes in a season in the Patriots' 34\u201320 win over the Buffalo Bills in their second divisional matchup.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://network.yardbarker.com/nfl/article_external/julian_edelmans_100_catch_1000_yard_season_for_patriots_did_not_come_easy/15416818 |title=Julian Edelman's 100-Catch, 1,000-Yard Season for Patriots Came After Fighting His Way Up Depth Chart - New England Patriots - NESN.com |website=NESN.com}}</ref> 2013 became a breakout season for Edelman as he played in all 16 games making 105 receptions for 1,056 receiving yards and 35 punt return opportunities for 374 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/E/EdelJu00/gamelog/2013/ |title=Julian Edelman 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> The Patriots won the AFC East and faced off against the [[2013 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] in the [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 43, Indianapolis Colts 22|Divisional Round]]. In the 43\u201322 victory, he had six receptions for 84 receiving yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201401110nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Indianapolis Colts at New England Patriots \u2013 January 11th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: Denver Broncos 26, New England Patriots 16|AFC Championship]] against the [[2013 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], he had 10 receptions for 89 receiving yards in the 26\u201316 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201401190den.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 New England Patriots at Denver Broncos \u2013 January 19th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nEdelman became a free agent after the 2013 season. On March 15, 2014, he re-signed with the Patriots on a four-year deal for $17 million.<ref>Services, ESPN.com News. \"Julian Edelman Returns To Patriots.\" ESPN. ESPN Internet Ventures, March 15, 2014. Web. March 15, 2014.</ref><ref>\"Report: Julian Edelman's Patriots Contract For Four Years, $17 Million.\" NESNcom. N.p., March 18, 2014. Web. April 15, 2014.</ref>\n\n===2014 season: First Super Bowl Championship===\nEdelman started 14 games for the Patriots in 2014. He had 92 receptions for 972 receiving yards, as well as four touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/julianedelman/238498/profile |title=Julian Edelman |website=NFL.com}}</ref> In a Week 9 matchup against the [[2014 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], Edelman returned a punt 84 yards for his fourth career return touchdown, passing [[Troy Brown]] for the most punt return touchdowns in Patriots history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000422089/article/tom-brady-patriots-dominate-broncos |title=Tom Brady, Patriots dominate Broncos |website=NFL.com}}</ref> In a Week 14 match up against the [[2014 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]], Edelman caught a pass from [[Tom Brady]] then broke two tackles and ran for 69 yards for a touchdown, it would be the final touchdown of the game that led the Patriots to a 23\u201314 win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2014120713/2014/REG14/patriots@chargers#tab=recap&menu=gameinfo%7CcontentId%3A0ap3000000440730 |title=Watch New England Patriots vs. San Diego Chargers [12/07/2014] - NFL.com |website=nfl.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Patriots won the AFC East and returned to the playoffs. Edelman recorded his first NFL touchdown pass on his first-ever NFL pass attempt in the Patriots' [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 35, Baltimore Ravens 31|Divisional Round]] game against the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]]. After receiving a [[lateral pass]] from Brady, Edelman threw a forward pass to [[Danny Amendola]], who scored a 51-yard touchdown to tie the game at 28\u201328. According to [[Pro-Football-Reference.com]], the pass was the longest touchdown pass thrown by a non-quarterback player in NFL playoff history, and makes Edelman one of six NFL players with a perfect postseason [[passer rating]] of 158.3.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/8mGDO |title=Pro-Football-Reference.com |date=February 7, 2015 |access-date=February 7, 2015}}</ref> In the [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 45, Indianapolis Colts 7|AFC Championship]] against the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he had nine receptions for 98 receiving yards in the 45\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501180nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Indianapolis Colts at New England Patriots \u2013 January 18th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Super Bowl XLIX]] against the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], Edelman led all receivers in yardage with 109 yards on nine receptions (teammate [[Shane Vereen]] had 11 receptions). His touchdown reception with 2:02 left in the fourth quarter\u2014his only touchdown reception of the postseason\u2014was the final go-ahead score of the game, putting the Patriots up 28\u201324. For the postseason as a whole, Edelman led all receivers in both receptions (26) and receiving yards (281).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/12649/year/2014/julian-edelman |title=Julian Edelman |website=ESPN.com |access-date=November 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201502010sea.htm |title=Super Bowl XLIX \u2013 Seattle Seahawks vs. New England Patriots \u2013 February 1st, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2015 season===\nOn September 10, Edelman started for the Patriots against the [[2015 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] in the season-opening game on ''Thursday Night Football''. He led the Patriots in yards and receptions, recording 11 receptions for 97 yards, in the 28\u201321 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509100nwe.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at New England Patriots \u2013 September 10th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> In the Patriots' second game of the season against the [[2015 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], Edelman got 11 catches, which made it the first time in his career he had back-to-back games with at least 10 catches. Edelman then caught four passes on five targets for 120 yards, against the [[2015 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] in Week 5.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/12649/julian-edelman |title=Julian Edelman |website=ESPN.com |access-date=November 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAgainst the [[2015 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] on November 15, Edelman suffered an injury to his [[fifth metatarsal]] on his left foot that required him to undergo foot surgery on November 16, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000580895/article/julian-edelman-suffers-broken-foot-could-return |title=Julian Edelman suffers broken foot, could return |last=Rosenthal |first=Gregg |date=November 15, 2015 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> He was expected to be back on the field in six to eight weeks, in time for the playoffs, though that was contingent on the recovery process.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.patriots.com/video/2015/11/16/rapoport-expectation-edelman-will-be-back-season |title=Rapoport: Expectation is that Edelman will be back this season |website=New England Patriots |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119045547/http://www.patriots.com/video/2015/11/16/rapoport-expectation-edelman-will-be-back-season |archive-date=November 19, 2015 |access-date=November 18, 2015}}</ref> Through nine games, Edelman had racked up 61 catches for 692 yards and seven touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/players/9496/ |title=Julian Edelman &#124; New England Patriots &#124; National Football League &#124; Yahoo! Sports |website=Sports.yahoo.com |access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Edelman returned for the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 27, Kansas City Chiefs 20|Divisional Round]] against the [[2015 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]]. Edelman had 10 catches for 100 yards to help the Patriots defeat the Chiefs 27\u201320 and advance to the AFC Championship game for the fifth consecutive year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601160nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Kansas City Chiefs at New England Patriots \u2013 January 16th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> In the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#AFC: Denver Broncos 20, New England Patriots 18|AFC Championship]], Edelman had 7 receptions for 53 yards, however the Patriots lost 20\u201318 to the [[2015 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601240den.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 New England Patriots at Denver Broncos \u2013 January 24th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> For his efforts in 2015, Edelman was ranked 87th on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000662082/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-87-Julian-Edelman |title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 87 Julian Edelman |website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2016 season: Second Super Bowl Championship===\nOn September 15, 2016, Edelman was fined $26,309 for a hit on a defenseless player where he hit linebacker [[Deone Bucannon]] helmet-to-helmet.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/new-england-patriots/2016/09/15/watch-the-hit-the-nfl-is-fining-julian-edelman-26000-for |title=Watch the hit the NFL is fining Julian Edelman $26,000 for |last=Dzen |first=Gary |publisher=boston.com |access-date=September 15, 2016}}</ref> In Week 13, against the [[2016 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], he had eight receptions for 101 yards in the 26\u201310 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612040nwe.htm |title=Los Angeles Rams at New England Patriots \u2013 December 4th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> In Week 17, Edelman got a block by newcomer wide receiver [[Michael Floyd]] on a catch and run that led to a career-long 77-yard touchdown in a 35\u201314 win over the [[2016 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nesn.com/2017/01/michael-floyd-delivers-block-of-the-year-to-spring-julian-edelman-for-touchdown/ |title=Michael Floyd Delivers Block Of The Year To Spring Julian Edelman For Touchdown |last=Cox, Zack |date=January 1, 2017 |website=NESN.com}}</ref> He finished the game with eight receptions for 151 yards including the 77-yard touchdown, earning him AFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.patriots.com/news/2017/01/04/julian-edelman-named-afc-offensive-player-week |title=Julian Edelman named AFC Offensive Player of the Week |date=January 4, 2017 |website=Patriots.com}}</ref> He became the first Patriots wide receiver to receive the award since [[Randy Moss]] in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4799378/julian-edelman-earns-afc-offensive-player-of-the-week-honor |title=Julian Edelman first Patriots WR to earn weekly award since Randy Moss \u2013 New England Patriots Blog |date=January 4, 2017 |website=Espn.com |access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> He finished the season with a new career-high 1,106 receiving yards on 98 catches. For his efforts in 2017, Edelman was ranked 71st by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000807270/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-71-Julian-Edelman |title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 71 Julian Edelman |website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\nIn the Patriots' [[2016\u201317 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 34, Houston Texans 16|Divisional Round]] victory against the [[2016 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], Edelman caught his 70th postseason pass, breaking Wes Welker's Patriots franchise record. Edelman recorded eight catches for 137 yards in the win<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201701140nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Houston Texans at New England Patriots - January 14th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> as the Patriots reached the AFC Championship Game for an NFL record sixth consecutive season. In the [[2016\u201317 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 36, Pittsburgh Steelers 17|AFC Championship]], Edelman caught eight passes for 118 yards in the 36\u201317 win over the [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201701220nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship - Pittsburgh Steelers at New England Patriots - January 22nd, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> The Patriots advanced to an NFL record ninth Super Bowl appearance.\n\nDuring [[Super Bowl LI]] against the [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Edelman made five catches for 87 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/gallery/sundays-10-best-super-bowl-performances-ranked-020617 |title=Sunday's 10 best Super Bowl performances, ranked |last=ET |first=2017 at 8:26a |website=FOX Sports}}</ref>  The highlight was an unusually difficult catch in the fourth quarter, where the pass was first tipped into the air by cornerback [[Robert Alford (American football)|Robert Alford]] and it appeared that it would fall incomplete, but Edelman and three defenders (Alford, [[Ricardo Allen]], and [[Keanu Neal]]) lunged at the ball, and, after it bounced off Alford's leg, Edelman made the reception just inches above the ground. It was ruled a catch on the field and withstood a challenge from Falcons head coach [[Dan Quinn (American football)|Dan Quinn]]. [[NFL Films]] called the play, which was chosen for the cover of ''[[Sports Illustrated]],''<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wire |first=SI |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2017/02/07/julian-edelman-patriots-super-bowl-sports-illustrated-cover |title=Julian Edelman featured on cover of SI's Super Bowl issue |work=SI.com |access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> \"the greatest catch in Super Bowl history\".<ref>{{Citation |last=NFL Films |title=Julian Edelman Makes the Greatest Catch in Super Bowl History {{!}} Do Your Job II {{!}} NFL Films |date=September 6, 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RRWl73-L3L0 |access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> Edelman's catch sustained a historic comeback for the Patriots, who trailed the Falcons 28\u20133 late in the third quarter before winning 34\u201328 in overtime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000783692/article/patriots-erase-deficit-defeat-falcons-in-super-bowl-li |title=New England Patriots win Super Bowl LI |last=Wesseling |first=Chris |publisher=NFL |access-date=February 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>Clarke, Liz. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/julian-edleman-catch-was-key-to-the-patriots-comeback/2017/02/06/041de6c0-ec2b-11e6-9973-c5efb7ccfb0d_story.html \"Julian Edelman's Super Bowl miracle catch gives Patriots answer to David Tyree\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', February 6, 2017</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201702050atl.htm |title=Super Bowl LI \u2013 New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons \u2013 February 5th, 2017 |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=August 6, 2017}}</ref> In the offseason, Edelman was ranked 71st by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000807270/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-71-Julian-Edelman |title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 71 Julian Edelman |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2017 season: Injured Season===\nOn June 8, 2017, Edelman signed a two-year, $11 million contract extension with the Patriots, with $9 million guaranteed through the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000814067/article/patriots-julian-edelman-agree-on-contract-extension |title=Patriots, Julian Edelman agree on contract extension |authors=Around the NFL staff |date=June 8, 2017 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> On August 25, in the team's third preseason game against the [[2017 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]], Edelman completely tore his [[Anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]], which prematurely ended his 2017 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000834786/article/patriots-lose-julian-edelman-torn-acl-for-season |title=Patriots' Julian Edelman out for season with torn ACL |authors=Around the NFL staff |date=August 26, 2017 |website=NFL.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000834790/article/tom-brady-others-react-to-julian-edelmans-torn-acl |title=Tom Brady, others react to Julian Edelman's torn ACL |authors=Around the NFL staff |publisher=NFL |access-date=August 26, 2017}}</ref> He was placed on injured reserve on September 2, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.patriots.com/news/2017/09/02/patriots-reach-53-man-limit |title=Patriots reach 53-man limit |date=September 2, 2017 |website=Patriots.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128033226/http://www.patriots.com/news/2017/09/02/patriots-reach-53-man-limit |archive-date=November 28, 2017}}</ref> Without Edelman, the Patriots finished 13\u20133 and reached [[Super Bowl LII]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2017.htm |title=2017 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> The Patriots lost 41\u201333 to the [[Philadelphia Eagles]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/super/2018/02/04/super-bowl-2018-score-philadelphia-eagles-new-england-patriots/305840002/ |title=Eagles dethrone Tom Brady, Patriots for first Super Bowl title in stunner |last=Jones |first=Lindsay H. |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 season: Super Bowl MVP===\n\nIn February 2018, it was reported that Edelman expected to be ready to play by the 2018 training camp.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.weei.com/blogs/ryan-hannable/julian-edelman-showing-more-encouraging-signs-returning-torn-acl |title=Julian Edelman showing more encouraging signs returning from torn ACL |last=Hannable |first=Ryan |website=WEEI.com |publisher=[[WEEI-FM|WEEI]] |access-date=May 1, 2018}}</ref> On June 7, it was announced that Edelman was expected to be suspended for four games due to a violation of the policy against using [[performance-enhancing drugs]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000936252/article/julian-edelman-facing-fourgame-suspension-for-peds |title=Julian Edelman facing four-game suspension for PEDs |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=June 7, 2018 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> On June 26, Edelman appealed the suspension;<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000938307/article/julian-edelman-appeals-fourgame-suspension-for-peds |title=Julian Edelman appeals four-game suspension for PEDs |last=Konblauch |first=Austin |publisher=NFL |access-date=June 26, 2018}}</ref> on July 3, his appeal was denied. Edelman missed the first four games of the season, and was activated on October 2. He played on ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' against the [[2018 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], where he caught seven passes for 57 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000939445/article/julian-edelmans-appeal-of-fourgame-suspension-denied |title=Julian Edelman's appeal of four-game suspension denied |last=Bergman |first=Jeremy |date=July 3, 2018 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> In Week 8, against the [[2018 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], he had nine receptions for 104 yards in the victory on ''Monday Night Football''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/patriots-julian-edelman-tops-century-mark-versus-bills/ |title=Patriots' Julian Edelman: Tops century mark versus Bills |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref> In Week 10, in a loss to the [[2018 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], he posted nine receptions for 104 yards once again.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://patriotswire.usatoday.com/2018/11/12/julian-edelman-on-loss-to-titans-you-better-learn-from-a-game-like-this/ |title=Julian Edelman on loss to Titans: 'You better learn from a game like this' |date=November 12, 2018 |website=Patriots Wire |language=en |access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref> On December 29, Edelman was fined $63,504 for three personal foul penalties in Week 16.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001004922/article/roundup-julian-edelman-fined-63k-for-penalties |title=Roundup: Julian Edelman fined $63K for penalties |publisher=NFL |access-date=December 29, 2018}}</ref> Overall, he finished the 2018 season with 74 receptions for 850 receiving yards and six touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/E/EdelJu00.htm |title=Julian Edelman 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> The Patriots finished with an 11\u20135 record and earned the #2 seed in the AFC in the playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2018/index.htm |title=2018 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 41, Los Angeles Chargers 28|Divisional Round]] against the [[2018 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]], he had nine receptions for 151 yards in the Patriots' 41\u201328 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/new-england-patriots/2019/01/13/julian-edelman-nfl-playoff-receptions-leaders-all-time |title=Julian Edelman moved up to second all-time in NFL postseason receptions |date=January 13, 2019 |website=Boston.com |language=en-US |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 37, Kansas City Chiefs 31 (OT)|AFC Championship]] against the [[2018 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], he had seven receptions for 96 yards in the 37\u201331 overtime victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/patriots-julian-edelman-totals-96-receiving-yards/ |title=Patriots' Julian Edelman: Totals 96 receiving yards |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> In [[Super Bowl LIII]], in a 13\u20133 victory over the [[2018 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], Edelman caught 10 passes on 12 targets for 141 yards, an effort for which he was named [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]]. He became the first wide receiver to win Super Bowl MVP since [[Santonio Holmes]] did so in [[Super Bowl XLIII]] in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/25919634 |title=Edelman 7th WR to win MVP after 10-catch night |date=February 4, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> He finished the postseason with 26 receptions for 388 yards, totals high enough to move him into second-place all-time in playoff receptions and receiving yards behind [[Jerry Rice]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/E/EdelJu00.htm |title=Julian Edelman Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 5, 2019}}</ref> Edelman is the first Jewish football player to be named Super Bowl MVP.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Julian-Edelman-is-Super-Bowl-MVP-579607 |title=Jerusalem Post Diaspora Julian Edelman Makes History as first Jewish Super Bowl MVP |last=JTA |date=February 4, 2019 |website=jpost |publisher=The Jerusalem Post |access-date=February 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nEdelman's MVP award drew criticism as it came in the same season he was suspended for using an unspecified [[performance-enhancing substance]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Felt |first=Hunter |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/feb/05/julian-edelmans-super-bowl-mvp-award-ped-suspension |title=Julian Edelman's Super Bowl MVP reveals the NFL's selective morality |date=February 5, 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=February 16, 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/ct-spt-bears-devin-hester-julian-edelman-patriots-ped-20190205-story.html |title=Devin Hester calls out Super Bowl MVP Julian Edelman for his PED use |last=Thompson |first=Phil |website=chicagotribune.com |language=en-US |access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/columnist/nancy-armour/2019/02/03/super-bowl-2019-mvp-julian-edelman-suspension/2765697002/ |title=Opinion: Super Bowl MVP Julian Edelman shouldn't even have been playing in the game |last=ByNancyArmour |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref> although some articles noted that much of the criticism came from [[Major League Baseball|baseball]] writers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nesn.com/2019/02/grumpy-baseball-writers-rip-super-bowl-mvp-julian-edelman-for-ped-use/ |title=Grumpy Baseball Writers Rip Super Bowl MVP Julian Edelman For PED Use |last=R |first=Dakota |last2=all |date=February 4, 2019 |website=NESN.com |language=en |access-date=February 19, 2019}}</ref> The NFL prohibits players suspended for PED use from receiving awards given by the league or the [[National Football League Players Association|NFL Players' Association]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/patriots/2018/06/11/julian-edelman-case-rife-with-questions-here-are-some-answers/crXuusn3bdYfPfKGiUHtLO/story.html |title=Julian Edelman case is rife with questions; here are some answers - The Boston Globe |last=Reporter |first=Ben Volin- |website=BostonGlobe.com |access-date=February 19, 2019}}</ref> In a post-Super Bowl interview, Edelman apologized, saying \"it'll never happen again.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/02/10/julian-edelman-patriots-mvp-nfl-fmia-peter-king/ |title=FMIA: From His Hollywood Haven, Julian Edelman Reflects on LIII MVP, His Path and Being a Perfect Patriot |last=King |first=Peter |date=February 11, 2019 |website=ProFootballTalk |language=en |access-date=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis performance in the 2018 playoffs has also led to debate over whether he should be considered a viable candidate for the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]], despite a relative lack of regular-season production.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bieler |first=Des |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/02/04/julian-edelman-is-your-super-bowl-mvp-is-he-hall-famer/ |title=After another stellar postseason, is Julian Edelman a Hall of Famer? |date=February 4, 2019 |work=Washington Post |access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019 season===\nOn May 21, 2019, Edelman signed a two-year, $18 million contract extension with the Patriots with $12 million guaranteed, keeping him under contract through the 2021 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001031417/article/julian-edelman-patriots-closing-in-on-extension |title=Patriots, Julian Edelman finalizing contract extension |last=Teope |first=Herbie |date=May 21, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref> In Week 1 against the [[2019 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]], Edelman caught six passes for 83 yards and threw one pass for 32 yards in the 33\u20133 win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127860 |title=Brady starts his 20th season by beating Steelers 33-3 |date=September 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 8, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 3 against the [[2019 New York Jets|New York Jets]], Edelman caught seven passes for 62 yards and his first receiving touchdown of the season in the 30\u201314 win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127861 |title=Brady, Patriots defense shine in 30-14 win over Jets |date=September 22, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 22, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Although, he suffered a rib injury in the second quarter that forced him out of the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nesn.com/2019/09/julian-edelman-injury-heres-latest-update-on-patriots-wide-receiver/ |title=Julian Edelman Injury: Here's Latest Update On Patriots Wide Receiver |last=London |first=Adam |date=September 22, 2019 |website=NESN.com |publisher=NESN |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> Edelman rebounded from his injury in Week 5 against the [[2019 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] in which he had eight receptions for 110 yards and a touchdown; he became the first Patriot to record at least 100 yards all season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.masslive.com/patriots/2019/10/julian-edelman-becomes-first-new-england-patriots-receiver-with-100-yard-game-this-season.html |title=Julian Edelman becomes first New England Patriots receiver with 100-yard game this season |last=Cotillo |first=Chris |date=October 6, 2019 |website=MassLive.com |publisher=MassLive |access-date=October 6, 2019}}</ref> In Week 6 against the [[2019 New York Giants|New York Giants]], Edelman recorded nine catches for 113 yards in the 35\u201314 win. In the game, Edelman surpassed [[Stanley Morgan]] for the third most receptions in Patriots history. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127917 |title=Patriots force 4 turnovers, beat Giants 35-14 to reach 6-0 |date=October 10, 2019 |access-date=October 10, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 8 against the [[2019 Cleveland Browns|Cleveland Browns]], Edelman caught eight passes for 78 yards and a season high two touchdowns in the 27\u201313 win. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127895 |title=Belichick wins 300th, perfect Patriots beat Browns 27-13 |date=October 27, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 27, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 11 against the [[2019 Philadelphia Eagles|Philadelphia Eagles]], Edelman caught five passes for 53 yards and threw a 15 yard touchdown pass to [[Phillip Dorsett II]] in the 17\u201310 win. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127897 |title=Edelman's TD pass leads Patriots over Eagles 17-10 |date=November 17, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 17, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 13 against the [[2019 Houston Texans|Houston Texans]] on ''[[NBC Sunday Night Football|Sunday Night Football]]'', Edelman caught six passes for 106 yards and a touchdown during the 28\u201322 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127967 |title=Watson throws 3 TDs, catches another; Texans top Pats 28-22 |date=December 1, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 1, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 17 against the [[2019 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]], Edelman caught three passes for 26 yards during the 27\u201324 loss.  In the game, Edelman reached 100 catches on the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127909 |title=Dolphins stun Patriots 27-24, denying NE first-round bye |date=December 29, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 29, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Overall, he finished the 2019 season with 100 receptions for 1,117 receiving yards and three receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/E/EdelJu00/gamelog/2019/ |title=Julian Edelman 2019 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 17, 2020}}</ref> In the AFC Wild Card game against the [[2019 Tennessee Titans|Tennessee Titans]], Edelman caught three passes for 30 yards and rushed two times for 12 yards and a touchdown during the 20\u201313 loss. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131036 |title=Derrick Henry, Titans stun Patriots 20-13 in wild-card upset |date=January 4, 2020 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 4, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==NFL statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|\n| Led the league\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n| [[List of Super Bowl champions|Won the Super Bowl]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f4c842; width:3em;\"|\n| [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award|Super Bowl MVP]]\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n===Regular season===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! colspan=\"2\"|Games !! colspan=\"5\"|Receiving !! colspan=\"5\"|Rushing !! colspan=\"5\"|Returning !! colspan=\"2\"|Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Ret !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2009 NFL season|2009]] !! [[2009 New England Patriots season|NE]] \n| 11 || 7 || 37 || 359 || 9.7 || 29 || 1 || 2 || 5 || 2.5 || 5 || 0 || 6 || 63 || 10.5 || 35 || 0 || 1 || 0\n|-\n! [[2010 NFL season|2010]] !! [[2010 New England Patriots season|NE]] \n| 15 || 3 || 7 || 86 || '''12.3''' || 40 || 0